{"title_page": "Graig Markel", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n{{fanpov|date=February 2009}}\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n\n'''Graig Markel''' is an American songwriter, producer and sound designer from [[Seattle, Washington]], United States.\n\n==Work==\nGraig is credited with creating the genre \"[[Broken Soul]]\", a mixture of [[downtempo]], [[Rock music|rock]], and [[R&B]] that has influenced artists such as [[Head Like a Kite]], [[Dirty Projectors]], [[Passion Pit]], [[Hot Chip]], [[Girl Talk (musician)|Girl Talk]], [[Her Space Holiday]], and more, through his solo work and current projects, the Animals at Night and Dead Ship Sailing.\n\nGraig is the owner of the Seattle-based studio, the Recovery Room. His list of credits include work with Band of Horses, Transmissionary Six, A-Frames, the Girls, Nada Surf, the Spits, Jim Carroll, Stone Gossard of Pearl Jam, Tiny Vipers, Arthur and Yu, the Grizzled Mighty, the Walkabouts, and many more.\n\nGraig has an affection for [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]] and even his latest records are available on vinyl records. Graig also designs and builds custom effect pedals for guitar, bass, and keyboard under the Recovery Effects brand name.\n\n==Bands==\n===New Sweet Breath===\nMarkel played in the late 1990s punk band New Sweet Breath.  They released several 7\" singles and 2 albums on Ringing Ear Records before signing to a major label in 1999.\n* 1995 \"Supersound Speedway\"\n* 1996 \"Demolition Theater\"\n\n===Tagging Satellites===\nMarkel produced and played guitar for Tagging Satellites from 1999-2001. They released 4 albums.\n* 1999 \"Shooting Down the Airwaves\"\n* 2000 \"Abstract Confessions\"\n* 2001 \"Risk of Flight\"\n* 2002 \"One Night Falls\"\n\n===Dead Ship Sailing===\nCurrent electro-rock project with Zera Marvel. \n* 2013 \"Dead Ship Sailing\"\n\n===The Animals at Night===\nCurrent broken soul project by Graig Markel. The Animals at Night recordings feature guest appearances by Jeremiah Green (Modest Mouse), Nabil Ayers and Eric Corson (Long Winters), Dave Einmo (Head Like a Kite), Larry Knechtel of the legendary Wrecking Crew (Beach Boys' \"Pet Sounds\", Phil Spector, Jackson 5, The Byrds, Simon and Garfunkel, and many more).\n* 2007 \"The Animals at Night\" (full length)\n* 2008 \"Rain Falls on Asphalt\"\n* 2011 \"Cut to Chase Chorus and Fade\"\n* 2013 \"The Animals at Night\" (EP)\n* 2016 \"The Animals at Night\" (full length)\n\n==Solo Work==\nMarkel's solo material includes collaborations and performances with [[Jeremiah Green]] ([[Modest Mouse]], [[Vells]]), [[Daniel G. Harmann]], and [[Jen Wood]] ([[The Postal Service]], [[Joan of Arc (band)|Joan of Arc]], [[Jeremy Enigk]], [[The Black Heart Procession]] and more).  He has worked with producer / engineer [[Aaron Prellwitz]] ([[Death Cab for Cutie]], [[Sun Kil Moon]], [[Red House Painters]], [[Neil Young]] and more).\n* 1999 \"Verses on Venus\"\n* 2000 \"Hard Grammar\"\n* 2000 \"July\" ([[-ismist Recordings]])\n* 2002 \"The Gospel Project\"\n* 2004 \"Tall Tales on Tape\"\n* 2007 \"Via Novella\"\n* 2007 \"Shipwrecked On the Shore\"\nShipwrecked On the Shore comes only in specially marked vinyl packs of Via Novella.\n* 2012 \"Graig Markel\"\n* 2014 \"Graig Markel and the 88th Street Band\"\n\nHe has also released separate EP's with pre-mature material.\n\n==References==\n* [http://graigmarkelmusic.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/sound-check/Content?oid=16895019/ The Stranger May, 2013]\n* [http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/156454-graig-markel-graig-markel/ Pop Matters April, 2012]\n* [http://www.inmusicwetrust.com/articles/56r24.html/ Review of \"The Gospel Project\" on In Music We Trust]\n* [http://blog.kexp.org/2013/02/22/song-of-the-day-the-animals-at-night-bare-feet-and-summer-teeth/ KEXP review February, 2013]\n* [http://www.seattleweekly.com/2010-08-04/music/the-short-list-the-week-s-recommended-shows// Seattle Weekly August 4, 2010]\n* [http://www.babysue.com/2012-Feb-LMNOP-Reviews.html#anchor95108/ Baby Sue February, 2012]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Markel, Graig}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Seattle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n{{fanpov|date=February 2009}}\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n\n'''Graig Markel''' is an American songwriter, producer and sound designer from [[Seattle, Washington]], United States.\n\n==Work==\nGraig is credited with creating the genre \"[[Broken Soul]]\", a mixture of [[downtempo]], [[Rock music|rock]], and [[R&B]] that has influenced artists such as [[Head Like a Kite]], [[Dirty Projectors]], [[Passion Pit]], [[Hot Chip]], [[Girl Talk (musician)|Girl Talk]], [[Her Space Holiday]], and more, through his solo work and current projects, the Animals at Night and Dead Ship Sailing.\n\nGraig is the owner of the Seattle-based studio, the Recovery Room. His list of credits include work with Band of Horses, Transmissionary Six, A-Frames, the Girls, Nada Surf, the Spits, Jim Carroll, Stone Gossard of Pearl Jam, Tiny Vipers, Arthur and Yu, the Grizzled Mighty, the Walkabouts, and many more.\n\nGraig has an affection for [[Gramophone record|Vinyl]] and even his latest records are available on vinyl records. Graig also designs and builds custom effect pedals for guitar, bass, and keyboard under the Recovery Effects brand name.\n\n==Bands==\n===New Sweet Breath===\nMarkel played in the late 90's punk band New Sweet Breath.  They released several 7\" singles and 2 albums on Ringing Ear Records before signing to a major label in 1999.\n* 1995 \"Supersound Speedway\"\n* 1996 \"Demolition Theater\"\n\n===Tagging Satellites===\nMarkel produced and played guitar for Tagging Satellites from 1999-2001. They released 4 albums.\n* 1999 \"Shooting Down the Airwaves\"\n* 2000 \"Abstract Confessions\"\n* 2001 \"Risk of Flight\"\n* 2002 \"One Night Falls\"\n\n===Dead Ship Sailing===\nCurrent electro-rock project with Zera Marvel. \n* 2013 \"Dead Ship Sailing\"\n\n===The Animals at Night===\nCurrent broken soul project by Graig Markel. The Animals at Night recordings feature guest appearances by Jeremiah Green (Modest Mouse), Nabil Ayers and Eric Corson (Long Winters), Dave Einmo (Head Like a Kite), Larry Knechtel of the legendary Wrecking Crew (Beach Boys' \"Pet Sounds\", Phil Spector, Jackson 5, The Byrds, Simon and Garfunkel, and many more).\n* 2007 \"The Animals at Night\" (full length)\n* 2008 \"Rain Falls on Asphalt\"\n* 2011 \"Cut to Chase Chorus and Fade\"\n* 2013 \"The Animals at Night\" (EP)\n* 2016 \"The Animals at Night\" (full length)\n\n==Solo Work==\nMarkel's solo material includes collaborations and performances with [[Jeremiah Green]] ([[Modest Mouse]], [[Vells]]), [[Daniel G. Harmann]], and [[Jen Wood]] ([[The Postal Service]], [[Joan of Arc (band)|Joan of Arc]], [[Jeremy Enigk]], [[The Black Heart Procession]] and more).  He has worked with producer / engineer [[Aaron Prellwitz]] ([[Death Cab for Cutie]], [[Sun Kil Moon]], [[Red House Painters]], [[Neil Young]] and more).\n* 1999 \"Verses on Venus\"\n* 2000 \"Hard Grammar\"\n* 2000 \"July\" ([[-ismist Recordings]])\n* 2002 \"The Gospel Project\"\n* 2004 \"Tall Tales on Tape\"\n* 2007 \"Via Novella\"\n* 2007 \"Shipwrecked On the Shore\"\nShipwrecked On the Shore comes only in specially marked vinyl packs of Via Novella.\n* 2012 \"Graig Markel\"\n* 2014 \"Graig Markel and the 88th Street Band\"\n\nHe has also released separate EP's with pre-mature material.\n\n==References==\n* [http://graigmarkelmusic.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/sound-check/Content?oid=16895019/ The Stranger May, 2013]\n* [http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/156454-graig-markel-graig-markel/ Pop Matters April, 2012]\n* [http://www.inmusicwetrust.com/articles/56r24.html/ Review of \"The Gospel Project\" on In Music We Trust]\n* [http://blog.kexp.org/2013/02/22/song-of-the-day-the-animals-at-night-bare-feet-and-summer-teeth/ KEXP review February, 2013]\n* [http://www.seattleweekly.com/2010-08-04/music/the-short-list-the-week-s-recommended-shows// Seattle Weekly August 4, 2010]\n* [http://www.babysue.com/2012-Feb-LMNOP-Reviews.html#anchor95108/ Baby Sue February, 2012]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Markel, Graig}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Seattle]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graig_Markel"}
{"title_page": "Dora Werzberg", "text_new": "{{short description|French nurse}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Dora Werzberg\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 5 September 1920\n| birth_place   = [[Strasbourg]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|04|01|1920|09|05}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Nurse <br/> Social Worker\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Dora Werzberg''' (5 September 1920 \u2013 1 April 2020) was a French nurse and social worker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hac.bard.edu/amor-mundi/in-memoriam-dora-amelan-2020-04-03|title=In Memoriam: Dora Amelan|date=3 April 2020|work=The Hannah Arendt Center for Politics and Humanities}}</ref> In 1942, she rescued Jewish children through [[\u0152uvre de secours aux enfants]] (OSE). She worked in the [[Camp de Rivesaltes]] and the [[Gurs internment camp]], and took care of children who had survived the Nazi concentration camps.\n==Biography==\nWerzberg was born in [[Strasbourg]], the daughter of Karl Werzberg and Gis\u00e8la Blum, who were Jewish emigrants from [[Poland]]. The family moved to [[Antwerp]] when Werzberg was ten, and stayed until the death of her mother and the invasion of [[Belgium]] by [[Nazi Germany]]. She then joined a Zionist youth movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ose-france.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Discours-de-JFG-Medaille-Dora-Amelan-Werzberg.pdf|title=Discours de Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Guthmann en l\u2019honneur de Dora Werzberg-Amelan|date=12 May 2016|work=\u0152uvre de secours aux enfants|language=French}}</ref> Werzberg had two sisters, Manda, who died of [[sepsis]] in 1942, and Simone Ben David, who died in [[Israel]] at age 86. Her cousins included [[Georges Loinger]] and [[Marcel Marceau]]. Werzberg went to the German Kommandantur to obtain papers to flee to the south of [[France]]. Her father was unable to obtain the papers, but fled to the ''[[Zone libre]]'' illegally. There, the Werzbergs settled in [[Limoges]], where her extended family was located.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ose-france.org/2016/05/lose-honore-dora-werzberg-amelan-lune-des-actrices-du-sauvetage-des-enfants-juifs-pendant-la-seconde-guerre-mondiale/|title=L'OSE honore Dora Werzberg Amelan, l'une des actrices du sauvetage des enfants juifs pendant la Seconde Guerre mondiale|date=12 May 2016|work=\u0152uvre de secours aux enfants|language=French}}</ref>\n\nHere, Werzberg worked for the OSE, the Camp de Rivesaltes, and, lastly, the Gurs internment camp until its closure in November 1943.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/judaism/184804/|title=The last voice from the French internment camps|date=27 April 2016|work=Jewish Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Garel|first=George|date=2012|title=Le sauvetage des enfants juifs par l\"OSE|trans-title= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ioSt_ptov-kC&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=Dora+Werzberg+%2B+Camp+de+Gurs&source=bl&ots=ldtGrBN-J6&sig=ACfU3U2gMri5zK9RqENakAAtVyO6Gb-OHA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjXueOdkdjhAhUFT98KHSxNBD0Q6AEwDHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Dora%20Werzberg%20%2B%20Camp%20de%20Gurs&f=false|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=\u00c9ditions Le Manuscrit|isbn=9782304040463}}</ref>\n\n==Distinction==\n*Knight of the [[Legion of Honour]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://journal.lemonde.fr/data/794/reader/reader.html?t=1585938715353#!794|title=Carnet|date=4 April 2020|work=Le Monde|language=French}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Werzberg, Dora}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Strasbourg]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French nurse}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Dora Werzberg\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 5 September 1920\n| birth_place   = [[Strasbourg]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|04|01|1920|09|05}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Nurse <br/> Social Worker\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Dora Werzberg''' (5 September 1920 \u2013 1 April 2020) was a French nurse and social worker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hac.bard.edu/amor-mundi/in-memoriam-dora-amelan-2020-04-03|title=In Memoriam: Dora Amelan|date=3 April 2020|work=The Hannah Arendt Center for Politics and Humanities}}</ref> In 1942, she rescued Jewish children through [[\u0152uvre de secours aux enfants]] (OSE). She worked in the [[Camp de Rivesaltes]] and the [[Gurs internment camp]], and took care of children who had survived the Nazi concentration camps.\n==Biography==\nWerzberg was born in [[Strasbourg]], the daughter of Karl Werzberg and Gis\u00e8la Blum, who were Jewish emigrants from [[Poland]]. The family moved to [[Antwerp]] when Werzberg was ten, and stayed until the death of her mother and the invasion of [[Belgium]] by [[Nazi Germany]]. She then joined a Zionist youth movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ose-france.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Discours-de-JFG-Medaille-Dora-Amelan-Werzberg.pdf|title=Discours de Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Guthmann en l\u2019honneur de Dora Werzberg-Amelan|date=12 May 2016|work=\u0152uvre de secours aux enfants|language=French}}</ref> Werzberg had two sisters, Manda, who died of [[sepsis]] in 1942, and Simone Ben David, who died in [[Israel]] at age 86. Her cousins included [[Georges Loinger]] and [[Marcel Marceau]]. Werzberg went to the German Kommandantur to obtain papers to flee to the south of [[France]]. Her father was unable to obtain the papers, but fled to the ''[[Zone libre]]'' illegally. There, the Werzbergs settled in [[Limoges]], where her extended family was located.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ose-france.org/2016/05/lose-honore-dora-werzberg-amelan-lune-des-actrices-du-sauvetage-des-enfants-juifs-pendant-la-seconde-guerre-mondiale/|title=L'OSE honore Dora Werzberg Amelan, l'une des actrices du sauvetage des enfants juifs pendant la Seconde Guerre mondiale|date=12 May 2016|work=\u0152uvre de secours aux enfants|language=French}}</ref>\n\nHere, Werzberg worked for the OSE, the Camp de Rivesaltes, and, lastly, the Gurs internment camp until its closure in November 1943.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/judaism/184804/|title=The last voice from the French internment camps|date=27 April 2016|work=Jewish Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Garel|first=George|date=2012|title=Le sauvetage des enfants juifs par l\"OSE|trans-title= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ioSt_ptov-kC&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=Dora+Werzberg+%2B+Camp+de+Gurs&source=bl&ots=ldtGrBN-J6&sig=ACfU3U2gMri5zK9RqENakAAtVyO6Gb-OHA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjXueOdkdjhAhUFT98KHSxNBD0Q6AEwDHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Dora%20Werzberg%20%2B%20Camp%20de%20Gurs&f=false|language=French|location=Paris|publisher=\u00c9ditions Le Manuscrit|isbn=9782304040463}}</ref>\n\n==Distinction==\n*Knight of the [[Legion of Honour]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://journal.lemonde.fr/data/794/reader/reader.html?t=1585938715353#!794|title=Carnet|date=4 April 2020|work=Le Monde|language=French}}</ref>\n==References==\n\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Strasbourg]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dora_Werzberg"}
{"title_page": "Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nAfter the initial [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)]], [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]], <section begin=Intro/>[[misinformation]], and [[disinformation]] emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention, treatment, and other aspects of the disease.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam|url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and misinformation was spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of some countries.<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth|title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMedical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease have circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name = \"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria|date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy/><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\"/><ref name=RunningList/><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\"/><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |publisher=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n\n==Combative efforts==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked as false some claims that have circulated on social media, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking lots of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water will prevent infection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by leading global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for overpriced health products, although price gouging is said to still be rampant on the platform.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation has been seen across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China and then later many of these same rumors spread to Korea and the United States prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung|author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==Conspiracy theories==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm/> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included Russian state media ([[RT (TV network)|RT]] and [[Channel One Russia]]), the British tabloid ''[[The Daily Mail]]'', and right-wing media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|author= Sharma, Gouri | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese biological weapon===\n\n====United States====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020 the [[BBC]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that claimed the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbc51271037\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online |date=January 30, 2020 |access-date=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal |first1=Kristian G. |last1=Andersen |first2=Andrew |last2=Rambaut |first3=W. Ian |last3=Lipkin |first4=Edward C. |last4=Holmes |first5=Robert F. |last5=Garry |title=The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2|journal=Nature Medicine|doi=10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9| date=March 17, 2020|pages=1\u20133 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9?fbclid=IwAR0cOVC4i9wyLuODURmxAxWWGOUm9RyzHmzTBA98jI_SR-ou8v-8_MLJgP4}}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\"/> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of bats and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner|publisher=[[Live Science]]| accessdate =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic\".<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme/conspiracy theory of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that made the virus that starts the [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. The theory saw a link between \"Racoon\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil''), and an anagram of \"Corona\" (the name of the virus).<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> The popularity of this theory attracted the attention of [[Snopes]], who disproved it by showing that the logo was not from the WIV but from Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd, located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai; Snopes pointed out that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil is Raccoon City.<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | date=January 29, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon,<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | accessdate=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while in the opinion of numerous medical experts there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese were using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2020, ''[[The Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson | date=February 14, 2020 | accessdate=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, did a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation aside, concerns on accidental leakage by the WIV remain.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{Cite journal|first=David|last=Cyranoski|title= Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens|date=February 22, 2017|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume=592 | issue=7642 | pages= 399\u2013400| bibcode= 2017Natur.542..399C| doi= 10.1038/nature.2017.21487|pmid= 28230144}}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" /> On February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the ''SCMP'' to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | date=February 6, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | date=February 7, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |accessdate= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\nIn the UK a conspiracy theory linking the coronavirus to the [[5G]] mobile phone network has led to a number of 5G masts apparently being set on fire. This may be linked to the involvement of the Chinese telecommunications company [[Huawei]] in developing the network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52172570|title=Coronavirus: Tech firms summoned over 'crackpot' 5G conspiracies|date=5 April 2020|website=BBC|access-date=April March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====India====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Ukraine====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===US biological weapon===\n====Russian accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archivedate=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] was very active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and many others. Sputnik branches in countries such as Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and Arab countries came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Iranian accusation====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's \"Biological Attack\" Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref> \nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the United Nations on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Chinese accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2014 and misinformation \u2014 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest state-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=2020-04-05|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles claim that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|accessdate=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|accessdate=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" >{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |accessdate=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Arab world====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n====Philippines====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus is a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master|date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Muslim===\n\n{{further|Islamophobia}}\nIn India Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a religious gathering. <ref>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta|title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha|title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back To A Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha|title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren\u2019t hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen|title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n===Antisemitic===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\"/>\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly|title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa|title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Professional conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]] has suggested the [[Rothschild family#Conspiracy thoeries|Rothschild family]] is \"fundamentally involved\" in using coronavirus to advance an agenda of societal domination and control.<ref>{{youtube|id=gMTZu6_TjU8|title=David Icke - The Truth Behind The Coronavirus Pandemic: COVID-19 Lockdown & The Economic Crash}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi|title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel|title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin|website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Spy operation===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact/> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\"/> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted/> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in an [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public\".<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Population control scheme===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by right-wing libertarians, NWO conspiracy theorists, and Christian Fundamentalists.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Nurse whistleblower===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao|access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Alleged leak of death toll===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington|website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation against Taiwan===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Medical==\n\nWidely circulated posts on social media have falsely claimed that, among other things:\n*'consuming boiled ginger with an empty stomach can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections|date=February 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'drinking lemon with water can be used to prevent the coronavirus and cancer, as it increases vitamin C levels',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online|date=March 10, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'holding one's breath for 10 seconds is an effective self-test for the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-viral-claims-holding-your-breath-can-test-covid-19 |title=World Health Organization refutes viral claims that holding your breath can test for COVID-19|date=March 4, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'hot saunas and hair dryers can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hot-air-saunas-hair-dryers-wont-prevent-or-treat-covid-19 |title=Hot air from saunas, hair dryers won't prevent or treat COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'an ancient Sri Lankan drink can prevent the coronavirus'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-claim-ancient-medicinal-herbs-are-effective-coronavirus-remedy |title=Health experts refute claim that ancient medicinal herbs are an effective coronavirus remedy|date=March 17, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'Turmeric and LifeBuoy brand soap'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2020/03/13/italy-indian-youth-swear-by-turmeric-crave-for-lifebuoy-to-keep-covid-19-at-bay.html |title=Indian youth swear by turmeric, crave for Lifebuoy to keep COVID-19 at bay|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Week}}</ref>\n*UV-C light, chlorine, and high (over 56&nbsp;\u00b0C) temperatures can be used on humans to kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-coronavirus-disinfectants|title=Misleading report claims UV light, chlorine and high temperatures can kill COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\nAll of the above claims have been disproven; for example, ginger has not been proven to cure any viral illness, and vitamin C has also not been proven to be effective against the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vaccine pre-existence===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocaine cure===\n\nSeveral viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a PSA debunking this claim, as did the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac|website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===African resistance===\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===5G===\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> The video of his allegations went viral;<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> both the claims and the video, which were endorsed by singer [[Keri Hilson]], were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne}}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] have had to resort to posting pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=3 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were torched, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \u201cjust nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\u201d<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref>  [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> \n\n[[YouTube]] announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> The discredited theories had been shared online by several celebrities,<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> including [[David Icke]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref>\n\n===Pets===\n\nHundreds of pets in China and elsewhere have been abandoned under the misbelief that common household pets, like dogs and cats, can get infected and spread the disease.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51614957|title=Coronavirus: Rescuing China's animals during the outbreak|work=BBC News|date=February 29, 2020|via=bbc.com|last1=Williams|first1=Sophie}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/15/asia/coronavirus-animals-pets-trnd/index.html|title=Cats and dogs abandoned at the start of the coronavirus outbreak are now starving or being killed|last=Kim|first=Allen|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5793363/china-coronavirus-covid19-abandoned-pets-wuhan/|title=China's Coronavirus Lockdown Sees Surge in Abandoned Pets|website=Time|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> There is little evidence that supports that dogs can get infected with the virus and spread it; however, dogs may get contaminated with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vetmed.illinois.edu/pet_column/coronavirus-pets/|title=Coronavirus and Pets: FAQs for Owners - Veterinary Medicine at Illinois|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/a-dog-in-hong-kong-tests-positive-for-the-coronavirus-who-confirms.html|title=A dog in Hong Kong tests positive for the coronavirus, WHO officials confirm|first=Noah|last=Higgins-Dunn|date=February 28, 2020|publisher=CNBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/03/13/dogs-pets-coronavirus/|title=Dog with 'low-level' coronavirus infection remains quarantined after blood test, Hong Kong officials say|first1=Karin|last1=Brulliard|website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/dont-panic-the-comprehensive-ars-technica-guide-to-the-coronavirus/2/#h5 |title=Don't Panic: The comprehensive Ars Technica guide to the coronavirus |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|first=Beth|last=Mole}}</ref>\n\n===Vegetarian immunity===\nSome organizations, including [[PETA]], and individuals made false claims on social media that eating meat made people susceptible to the virus.<ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|accessdate=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn India, a false rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Methanol===\nIran has reported [[methanol]] consumption incidents under the false belief that it would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/> [[Rum-running|bootleg alcohols]] that contain methanol, which is an industrial alcohol, were often consumed since [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\"/> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\"/> Iranian social media had circulated a story on British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of [[ethanol|alcohol]]-based [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n===Efficacy of hand sanitiser===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially does kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac|date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cruise ship safe from infection===\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Scientists caution that this is possible, but not guaranteed.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on Feb. 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>\n\n===Country-based===\n\n====Brazil====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur|date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine Tamiflu, according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|accessdate=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Estonia====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina|date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, will continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/>\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis|website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/>\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although the alleged miracle drug is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\n====India====\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Parliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Misinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/>\n\n====Nigeria====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref>https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually bleach) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz| title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren| title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> The New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason|date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe  US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Venezuela====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===American===\n\n{{see also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been \"community-spreading\" in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal|date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palca|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] is false (that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number.\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson|website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak is exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it is safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied he made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, despite footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House has accused the media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus to destabilize the administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment because the first case of community spread of the virus was confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]] with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the fatality rate for seasonal flu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\". This came right after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him it would actually take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating: \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to vaccines requiring multiple rounds of tests before being approved for the public's use.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump wrongly blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions In Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=April 2020}} For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49591617778).jpg|thumb|240px|President Trump speaks during a press briefing on the COVID-19 pandemic]]\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", senior health official Anthony Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23/> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\". The companies were in fact not producing ventilators. The [[Associated Press]] news agency estimated it would take at least several months for the carmaker companies to change their factories' production abilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City,  claimed that it was a misperception that the disease \"hangs in the air\" as it \"takes direct person-to-person contact\",  \"If you\u2019re under 50 and you\u2019re healthy, (...) there\u2019s very little threat\". He pledged to keep schools open, even if pupils are sick. He declined to cancel St. Patrick\u2019s Day parade and then did. He resisted calls to cancel regular street sweeping and then did. He gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David|date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the  [[Hoover Institution]] who in series of articles  consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac|website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mexican===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese===\n====Mishandling of crisis====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] on December 30, 2019 revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later research published on January 20, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Origin of virus====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/>\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng|url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> According to the ''Washington Post'', many online Chinese have also criticized the US and to a lesser extent South Korea and Italian governments.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref>{{cite web |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost/> who criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/>\n\n====Statistics on fatalities====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other heath complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith}}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau - Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Some articles<ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Iranian===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means.\u201d.<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|work=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuban===\n\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper [[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]].{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Russian===\n\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilian===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb - BBC News |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Scams==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n===Bat soup===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=bru-14bc/>\n\n===''Simpsons'' prediction===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras|website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Corona beer misassociation===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson|date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha|date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand, but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al|website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Hospital conditions===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about the inadequacies in the working conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1=Carville |first1=Olivia |last2=Court |first2=Emma |last3=Brown |first3=Kristen V |title=Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website=Bloomberg | date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Collman |first1=Ashley |title=Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website=Business Insider |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil/>\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who?|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll|title=Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first=Caroline|last=Orr|date=April 1, 2020|website=National Observer|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Return of wildlife===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> \n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry |first=Terry Jr. |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned [[China News Service]] debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[Humpback whale|humpback whales]] allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=2020-04-05|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Lions freed on the streets===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in Moscow was passed around as if it were true.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nAfter the initial [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)]], [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]], <section begin=Intro/>[[misinformation]], and [[disinformation]] emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention, treatment, and other aspects of the disease.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | accessdate=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam|url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and misinformation was spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of some countries.<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth|title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMedical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease have circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name = \"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria|date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy/><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\"/><ref name=RunningList/><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\"/><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |publisher=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n\n==Combative efforts==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked as false some claims that have circulated on social media, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking lots of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water will prevent infection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by leading global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for overpriced health products, although price gouging is said to still be rampant on the platform.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation has been seen across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China and then later many of these same rumors spread to Korea and the United States prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung|author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==Conspiracy theories==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm/> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included Russian state media ([[RT (TV network)|RT]] and [[Channel One Russia]]), the British tabloid ''[[The Daily Mail]]'', and right-wing media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|author= Sharma, Gouri | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese biological weapon===\n\n====United States====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020 the [[BBC]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that claimed the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbc51271037\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online |date=January 30, 2020 |access-date=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal |first1=Kristian G. |last1=Andersen |first2=Andrew |last2=Rambaut |first3=W. Ian |last3=Lipkin |first4=Edward C. |last4=Holmes |first5=Robert F. |last5=Garry |title=The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2|journal=Nature Medicine|doi=10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9| date=March 17, 2020|pages=1\u20133 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9?fbclid=IwAR0cOVC4i9wyLuODURmxAxWWGOUm9RyzHmzTBA98jI_SR-ou8v-8_MLJgP4}}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\"/> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of bats and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner|publisher=[[Live Science]]| accessdate =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic\".<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme/conspiracy theory of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that made the virus that starts the [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. The theory saw a link between \"Racoon\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil''), and an anagram of \"Corona\" (the name of the virus).<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> The popularity of this theory attracted the attention of [[Snopes]], who disproved it by showing that the logo was not from the WIV but from Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd, located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai; Snopes pointed out that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil is Raccoon City.<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | date=January 29, 2020 | accessdate=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon,<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | accessdate=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while in the opinion of numerous medical experts there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese were using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2020, ''[[The Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson | date=February 14, 2020 | accessdate=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, did a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation aside, concerns on accidental leakage by the WIV remain.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{Cite journal|first=David|last=Cyranoski|title= Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens|date=February 22, 2017|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume=592 | issue=7642 | pages= 399\u2013400| bibcode= 2017Natur.542..399C| doi= 10.1038/nature.2017.21487|pmid= 28230144}}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" /> On February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the ''SCMP'' to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | date=February 6, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | date=February 7, 2020 | accessdate=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |accessdate= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\nIn the UK a conspiracy theory linking the coronavirus to the [[5G]] mobile phone network has led to a number of 5G masts apparently being set on fire. This may be linked to the involvement of the Chinese telecommunications company [[Huawei]] in developing the network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52172570|title=Coronavirus: Tech firms summoned over 'crackpot' 5G conspiracies|date=5 April 2020|website=BBC|access-date=April March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====India====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Ukraine====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===US biological weapon===\n====Russian accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng |date=February 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archivedate=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] was very active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and many others. Sputnik branches in countries such as Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and Arab countries came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Iranian accusation====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's \"Biological Attack\" Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref> \nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the United Nations on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Chinese accusation====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2014 and misinformation \u2014 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest state-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=2020-04-05|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles claim that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|accessdate=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|accessdate=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" >{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |accessdate=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Arab world====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n====Philippines====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus is a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master|date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Muslim===\n\n{{further|Islamophobia}}\nIn India Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a religious gathering. <ref>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020 AT 12:37 PM EDT|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta|title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha|title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back To A Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[BuzzfeedNews]]|date=April 3, 2020, at 3:40 p.m. ET|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha|title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren\u2019t hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=28th March 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.\n<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen|title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=Sun 5 Apr 2020 15.53 BSTLast modified on Sun 5 Apr 2020 20.15 BST|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n===Antisemitic===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\"/>\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly|title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa|title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Professional conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]] has suggested the [[Rothschild family#Conspiracy thoeries|Rothschild family]] is \"fundamentally involved\" in using coronavirus to advance an agenda of societal domination and control.<ref>{{youtube|id=gMTZu6_TjU8|title=David Icke - The Truth Behind The Coronavirus Pandemic: COVID-19 Lockdown & The Economic Crash}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi|title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel|title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin|website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Spy operation===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact/> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\"/> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted/> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in an [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public\".<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Population control scheme===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by right-wing libertarians, NWO conspiracy theorists, and Christian Fundamentalists.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Nurse whistleblower===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao|access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Alleged leak of death toll===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington|website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation against Taiwan===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Medical==\n\nWidely circulated posts on social media have falsely claimed that, among other things:\n*'consuming boiled ginger with an empty stomach can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections|date=February 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'drinking lemon with water can be used to prevent the coronavirus and cancer, as it increases vitamin C levels',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online|date=March 10, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'holding one's breath for 10 seconds is an effective self-test for the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-viral-claims-holding-your-breath-can-test-covid-19 |title=World Health Organization refutes viral claims that holding your breath can test for COVID-19|date=March 4, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'hot saunas and hair dryers can kill the coronavirus',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hot-air-saunas-hair-dryers-wont-prevent-or-treat-covid-19 |title=Hot air from saunas, hair dryers won't prevent or treat COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'an ancient Sri Lankan drink can prevent the coronavirus'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-claim-ancient-medicinal-herbs-are-effective-coronavirus-remedy |title=Health experts refute claim that ancient medicinal herbs are an effective coronavirus remedy|date=March 17, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n*'Turmeric and LifeBuoy brand soap'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2020/03/13/italy-indian-youth-swear-by-turmeric-crave-for-lifebuoy-to-keep-covid-19-at-bay.html |title=Indian youth swear by turmeric, crave for Lifebuoy to keep COVID-19 at bay|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Week}}</ref>\n*UV-C light, chlorine, and high (over 56&nbsp;\u00b0C) temperatures can be used on humans to kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-coronavirus-disinfectants|title=Misleading report claims UV light, chlorine and high temperatures can kill COVID-19|date=March 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\nAll of the above claims have been disproven; for example, ginger has not been proven to cure any viral illness, and vitamin C has also not been proven to be effective against the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/doctors-refute-misleading-online-claim-consuming-boiled-ginger-can-cure-novel-coronavirus-infections |title=Doctors refute misleading online claim that consuming boiled ginger can cure novel coronavirus infections &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claims-drinking-water-lemon-can-prevent-covid-19-circulate-online |title=False claims that drinking water with lemon can prevent COVID-19 circulate online &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vaccine pre-existence===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocaine cure===\n\nSeveral viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a PSA debunking this claim, as did the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac|website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===African resistance===\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===5G===\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> The video of his allegations went viral;<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> both the claims and the video, which were endorsed by singer [[Keri Hilson]], were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne}}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] have had to resort to posting pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=3 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were torched, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \u201cjust nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\u201d<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref>  [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> \n\n[[YouTube]] announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> The discredited theories had been shared online by several celebrities,<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> including [[David Icke]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref>\n\n===Pets===\n\nHundreds of pets in China and elsewhere have been abandoned under the misbelief that common household pets, like dogs and cats, can get infected and spread the disease.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51614957|title=Coronavirus: Rescuing China's animals during the outbreak|work=BBC News|date=February 29, 2020|via=bbc.com|last1=Williams|first1=Sophie}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/15/asia/coronavirus-animals-pets-trnd/index.html|title=Cats and dogs abandoned at the start of the coronavirus outbreak are now starving or being killed|last=Kim|first=Allen|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5793363/china-coronavirus-covid19-abandoned-pets-wuhan/|title=China's Coronavirus Lockdown Sees Surge in Abandoned Pets|website=Time|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> There is little evidence that supports that dogs can get infected with the virus and spread it; however, dogs may get contaminated with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vetmed.illinois.edu/pet_column/coronavirus-pets/|title=Coronavirus and Pets: FAQs for Owners - Veterinary Medicine at Illinois|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/a-dog-in-hong-kong-tests-positive-for-the-coronavirus-who-confirms.html|title=A dog in Hong Kong tests positive for the coronavirus, WHO officials confirm|first=Noah|last=Higgins-Dunn|date=February 28, 2020|publisher=CNBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/03/13/dogs-pets-coronavirus/|title=Dog with 'low-level' coronavirus infection remains quarantined after blood test, Hong Kong officials say|first1=Karin|last1=Brulliard|website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/dont-panic-the-comprehensive-ars-technica-guide-to-the-coronavirus/2/#h5 |title=Don't Panic: The comprehensive Ars Technica guide to the coronavirus |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|first=Beth|last=Mole}}</ref>\n\n===Vegetarian immunity===\nSome organizations, including [[PETA]], and individuals made false claims on social media that eating meat made people susceptible to the virus.<ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|accessdate=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn India, a false rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Methanol===\nIran has reported [[methanol]] consumption incidents under the false belief that it would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/> [[Rum-running|bootleg alcohols]] that contain methanol, which is an industrial alcohol, were often consumed since [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\"/> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\"/> Iranian social media had circulated a story on British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of [[ethanol|alcohol]]-based [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n===Efficacy of hand sanitiser===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially does kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac|date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cruise ship safe from infection===\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Scientists caution that this is possible, but not guaranteed.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on Feb. 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>\n\n===Country-based===\n\n====Brazil====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur|date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine Tamiflu, according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|accessdate=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Estonia====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina|date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, will continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/>\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis|website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/>\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although the alleged miracle drug is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\n====India====\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Parliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|accessdate=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Misinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/>\n\n====Nigeria====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref>https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually bleach) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz| title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren| title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| accessdate=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> The New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason|date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe  US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Venezuela====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===American===\n\n{{see also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been \"community-spreading\" in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal|date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palca|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] is false (that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number.\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson|website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak is exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it is safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied he made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, despite footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House has accused the media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus to destabilize the administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment because the first case of community spread of the virus was confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]] with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the fatality rate for seasonal flu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\". This came right after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him it would actually take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating: \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to vaccines requiring multiple rounds of tests before being approved for the public's use.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump wrongly blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions In Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=April 2020}} For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49591617778).jpg|thumb|240px|President Trump speaks during a press briefing on the COVID-19 pandemic]]\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", senior health official Anthony Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23/> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\". The companies were in fact not producing ventilators. The [[Associated Press]] news agency estimated it would take at least several months for the carmaker companies to change their factories' production abilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City,  claimed that it was a misperception that the disease \"hangs in the air\" as it \"takes direct person-to-person contact\",  \"If you\u2019re under 50 and you\u2019re healthy, (...) there\u2019s very little threat\". He pledged to keep schools open, even if pupils are sick. He declined to cancel St. Patrick\u2019s Day parade and then did. He resisted calls to cancel regular street sweeping and then did. He gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David|date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the  [[Hoover Institution]] who in series of articles  consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac|website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mexican===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese===\n====Mishandling of crisis====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] on December 30, 2019 revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later research published on January 20, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Origin of virus====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/>\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng|url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> According to the ''Washington Post'', many online Chinese have also criticized the US and to a lesser extent South Korea and Italian governments.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref>{{cite web |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost/> who criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/>\n\n====Statistics on fatalities====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other heath complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith}}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau - Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Some articles<ref>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | accessdate=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | accessdate=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Iranian===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means.\u201d.<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|work=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuban===\n\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper [[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]].{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Russian===\n\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilian===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb - BBC News |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Scams==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n===Bat soup===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=bru-14bc/>\n\n===''Simpsons'' prediction===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras|website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Corona beer misassociation===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson|date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha|date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand, but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al|website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Hospital conditions===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about the inadequacies in the working conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1=Carville |first1=Olivia |last2=Court |first2=Emma |last3=Brown |first3=Kristen V |title=Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website=Bloomberg | date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Collman |first1=Ashley |title=Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website=Business Insider |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil/>\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who?|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll|title=Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first=Caroline|last=Orr|date=April 1, 2020|website=National Observer|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Return of wildlife===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> \n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry |first=Terry Jr. |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned [[China News Service]] debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[Humpback whale|humpback whales]] allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=2020-04-05|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Lions freed on the streets===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in Moscow was passed around as if it were true.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "name_user": "Brainulator9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnti-Muslim:cite fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misinformation_related_to_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "John Hardon", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = [[Servant of God]] <br> John Anthony Hardon, [[Society of Jesus|S.J.]]\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1914|6|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Midland, Pennsylvania|Midland]], [[Pennsylvania (state)|Pennsylvania]], United States\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2000|12|30|1914|6|18|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Clarkston, Michigan|Clarkston]], [[Michigan (state)|Michigan]], United States\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| occupation         = Priest\n| title              = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| networth           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n{{jesuit}}\n\n'''John Anthony Hardon''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Society of Jesus|SJ]]}} (June 18, 1914 \u2013 December 30, 2000) was an American [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] [[priest]], writer, and [[theologian]]. He is recognized by the [[Catholic Church]] as a [[Servant of God]]<ref name=\"Register\">{{cite news| title=The Cause for Father Hardon: Sanctity Made in America, Part 2| first=Charlotte| last=Hays| url=http://www.ncregister.com/site/article/the-cause-for-father-hardon/| newspaper=[[National Catholic Register]]| date=29 October 2010|accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJohn Anthony Hardon was born in 1914 to a devout Catholic family in [[Midland, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" /> When he was a year old, his 27-year-old father died in an industrial accident when the scaffolding collapsed under him as he moved to secure a steel beam dangling dangerously over his co-workers.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /><ref name=\"Pew\">{{cite web|title=Father Hardon will indeed be a hard act to follow|url=http://www.dailycatholic.org/issue/2001Jan/jan5ed.htm|date=January 5, 2001|publisher=Catholic Pewpoint}}</ref> After the accident Hardon was raised by his 26-year-old mother Anna (n\u00e9e Jevin) Hardon, who never remarried \"out of concern for the influence a possible stepfather might have on her son's vocation.\"<ref name=\"Register\" /><ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> They moved to [[Cleveland, Ohio]],<ref name=\"Review\"/> where they lived \"in the shadows of the iron and steel mills\".<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> John Janaro, a biographer of Hardon, described Anna as \"a woman of deep faith, a [[Third Order of Saint Francis|Franciscan tertiary]] who embraced her poverty and her difficult circumstances with courage and grace.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Anna \"attended daily Mass and received Holy Communion\" and her home \"had sacred pictures, a family holy water font, and a good deal of spiritual conversation.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> The Hardons could not afford a telephone and \"in fact they seldom bought a newspaper.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ewtn.com/library/PRIESTS/HARDON.TXT|title=Fr. John Hardon|author=John Janaro|publisher=EWTN}}</ref>\n\nHardon was Anna's only child, and she supported him by cleaning offices in Cleveland, often working nights. Janaro reports that as a child Hardon was \"willful and self-possessed; he was determined that no one was going to tell him what to do\"; but he was soon affected by his mother's devoted example.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Hardon would often recall that his mother told him that she \"taught him to kneel before he could walk\" and the very purpose of knees \"are for kneeling to pray before God\".<ref name=\"Pew\" /> When he was four, Anna took him to his first all night vigil at Our Lady of Consolation parish in Carey, Ohio.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> She made a bed for him on the first pew, and prayed throughout the night on her knees as he slept.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> At the age of six he was instructed by a Sister Benedicta who told her students \"Whatever you ask Our Lord on your First Communion day, you will receive.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> That same year as he received First Holy Communion Hardon made a request to Jesus, \"Make me a priest.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Thereafter the young Hardon attended daily Mass with his mother.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> At the age of eight he received the sacrament of Confirmation calling on the Holy Spirit to give him \"the grace of martyrdom.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" />\n\nFor added income Hardon's mother took in two young [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] girls as boarders<ref name=\"Pew\" /> named Judith and Susan.<ref name=Real>{{cite web|title=Retreat on the Credo, Faith in the Holy Catholic Church and the Communion of Saints|author=Fr. John A. Hardon, S.J.|url=http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/Church_Dogma/Church_Dogma_052.htm}}</ref> Young Hardon at the age of three<ref name=Real/> protested that he had to abstain from meat on Friday but the boarders, which he called his \"sisters\" did not. In response his mother gave the girls a choice saying \"My boy is growing up: he's asking embarrassing questions. Would you mind either abstaining from eating meat on Friday or find yourselves somewhere else to board?\"<ref name=Real/> The girls choose to abstain.<ref name=Real/> After having them get permission from their minister they were included in the fast.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> It was this early relationship with these borders who were \"staunch Lutherans\" (who lived with them for at least eight years<ref name=Real/>) that Hardon would later cite as affecting his thinking, recalling in later life \"Years before the Ecumenical Movement I had come to respect and cherish Protestants.\"<ref name=Real/>\n\n=== Early schooling ===\nHardon excelled in schooling and was often at the top of his classes at St. Wendelin School (which he had to walk two miles to reach).<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />  His ability to hold the attention of a crowd was seen early when in sixth grade he gave a one-man show to his class entitled \"Pockets\" and \"For one solid hour he kept the audience laughing with his explanations of what he carried in his pockets.\"<ref name=\"Pew\" />\n\nDuring a Church History class in eighth grade Hardon was inspired on hearing about the preaching of [[Peter Canisius|St. Peter Canisius]], a Jesuit priest in the 16th century who combated the [[Protestant Reformation]] in Germany. Through this Hardon became impressed with the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] order.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHis mother did not have the funds to send him to a Jesuit High School, so he attended the diocesan high school of Cathedral Latin 15 miles from his home where he was taught by the [[Marist Brothers|Brothers of Mary]].<ref name=\"hardonsj\">{{cite web|title=Rev. John A. Hardon - Biography|author=Dr. Elizabeth Mitchell|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/biography}}</ref>\n\nWorrying about leaving his mother on her own Hardon did not seriously consider the priesthood immediately after high school.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Upon graduation \"With the help of savings his mother had put aside specifically for his future\" he attended [[John Carroll University]], a Jesuit university in a suburb of Cleveland.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> To travel there from his mother's home he had to ride the streetcar \"a distance of three to four hours daily.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" />\n\nDuring his first two years of college, Hardon intended to become a medical doctor. At University, he came even more strongly under the influence of the Jesuits. Janaro writes:\n\n{{quote|The Jesuit presence had a profound impact on him. There was a certain strength about the Jesuits, a \"manliness\" that John had never experienced at home because he never knew his father. Also their mental discipline impressed him; it motivated him to major in philosophy and it began to shape his approach to spirituality through the direction of Father LeMay, a brilliant and discerning man who saw in John great potential.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />}}\n\nElizabeth Mitchell writes that \"under the guidance of his priestly adviser, Hardon began, in his third year of studies, to discern more clearly his own call to the priesthood\".<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />  It was LeMay who guided Hardon to change \"his course of studies to include Latin, philosophy, and college theology.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Hardon continued his studies until he earned his Bachelor of Arts degree from John Carrol University in 1936.<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />\n\n=== Entering the Jesuits ===\nIt did not appear that he would be able to join the Jesuits due to his mother's worsening health, whom he felt duty bound to look after. Seeking both to fulfill his duty to his mother and to serve others, he had applied and been accepted to Ohio State Medical School.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />  While he felt that he did not have a vocation to the priesthood, Fr. LeMay, his Jesuit spiritual adviser, \"did not agree with John's assessment of his situation\" and held that \"John did indeed have a priestly vocation\".<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> His mother, aware that his concern for her health was influencing his decision, told him that \"the very same God who was calling him would guard every hair on his mother's head.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> She also told him \"if the reason he was going to marry was so that she would not be alone without anyone to care for her, he was not to be concerned.\"<ref name=\"Pew\" /> Considering his dream of matrimony \"the thought of marriage and family was overwhelmed by a realization of the spiritual family that springs up around a priest who brings the life of Christ to so many people.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nHardon announced his decision to pursue the priesthood to a girl named Jo who had been his friend since grade school when they sat next to each other.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> They had been dating seriously and discussed marriage on several occasions<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> and Hardon had \"weighed the possibility of becoming engaged.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> He broke the news to her at a restaurant in downtown Cleveland.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Jo did not take the news well, breaking down in tears and crying throughout the meal.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon entered the Jesuit novitiate on September 1, 1936, \"breaking the heart of a girl he loved, and loved him in return.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\"/>\n\nHardon's health difficulties continued he later recalled \"When I entered the Novitiate, in one month they put me in the hospital I thought they were gonna throw me out of the order.\"<ref name=Sacrifice>{{cite web|title=What is Sacrifice?|author=John Hardon|url=http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/Mass/Mass_010.htm|date=August 3, 1982}}</ref> Hardon recovered and continued his studies.\n\nTwo months into his novitiate Hardon confessed to Fr. LeMay that he felt he had abandoned his mother when she needed him most. LeMay told him \"John, you belong in the Society of Jesus. What you are experiencing is a temptation. Put it out of your\nmind.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> To avoid further temptations Hardon continued regularly to correspond with his mother but scrupulously avoided visiting her for seven years until ordered to do so by his superior.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon was deeply affected by the accidental drowning of a fellow seminarian when a group of them were on a summer lakeshore vacation.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> As a result of this he refused to take vacations for the rest of his life.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\n== Priesthood ==\nHaving [[Jesuit formation|entered the Society of Jesus as a novice]] on September 1, 1936 Hardon took a special interest in theology and teaching while studying at West Baden College in [[West Baden Springs, Indiana]]. During these studies he produced his first published article in 1941 concerning the study of Latin. Worrying that his love of theology might lead him to pursue it out of his own willfulness at the cost of obedience he \"determined not to request further theological study; he would leave the determination of his future completely in the hands of the Holy Spirit.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon continued to study and obtained a master's degree in philosophy at [[Loyola University Chicago]] in 1941.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" />\n\nOn June 18, 1947 (his 33rd birthday) he was ordained to the priesthood with his mother in attendance.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> The two Lutheran boarders of Hardon's childhood had remained close to the family and attended his ordination<ref name=Real/> and first Mass.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Within a year of seeing her son enter the priesthood Hardon's mother died.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nHardon took it as a sign of divine favor when his superiors, with no prompting from him, ordered him to attend the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in [[Rome]] to continue his study of theology (from 1949 to 1951).<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /><ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nWhile studying at Rome, he was appointed director of the graduate library. At one point his superior ordered him to retrieve all of the volumes held on loan by other graduate students that were [[Index Librorum Prohibitorum|declared heretical]] by the Catholic Church. Hardon later recalled:\n\n{{quote|Before I had retrieved one-half of the heretical books, I had become the agent of orthodoxy and therefore the sworn enemy of the modernists, who were updating the Catholic faith to its [[Modernism (Roman Catholicism)|modernist]] theology. I had doors slammed in my face. I lost friends whom I had considered believers....[this experience] taught me that the faith I had so casually learned could be preserved only by the price of a living martyrdom. This faith, I was to find out, is a precious treasure that cannot be preserved except at a heavy price. The price is nothing less than to confess what so many others either openly or covertly denied.\"<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />}}\n\nHe received his [[Doctor of Sacred Theology]] degree from the Gregorian University after finishing his doctoral dissertation on St. [[Robert Bellarmine]] entitled ''A Comparative Study of Bellarmine's Doctrine on the Relation of Sincere Non-Catholics to the Catholic Church''. Later in his life, he stated, \u201cI could not have chosen a better subject in preparation for a lifetime of teaching Catholic doctrine.\u201d<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/biography |title=Biography &#124; Father John A. Hardon, SJ |publisher=Hardonsj.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-18}}</ref> That same year, 1951, he received the Papal Medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ordained to Sacrifice|url=http://credo.stormloader.com/Saints/hardon.htm|access-date=2012-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020809152359/http://credo.stormloader.com/Saints/hardon.htm|archive-date=2002-08-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDue to lifelong health problems, including asthma, Hardon was forced to return to America in 1951, where he joined the faculty of West Baden College teaching theology to Jesuit students. Hardon was denied his request to be a missionary to post-War Japan (at the newly opened Jesuit University in Tokyo) due to his health.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Determined to be of some service for this endeavor, Hardon began to study [[comparative religion]].<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> During his studies of oriental religions he believed there were \"not only areas that were compatible with Christianity but also sections of thought that were clearly influenced in a direct manner by contact with the Christian message.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon began using his extensive knowledge of Asian customs and religions to train missionaries for that region.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nDuring this time Hardon pronounced his final vows on February 2, 1953 including the special [[Fourth vow|Jesuit vow of unwavering fidelity]] to the pope.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nIn an effort to understand Protestantism he worked on a book released in 1956 entitled ''Protestant Churches in America'', which was met with critical acclaim even among Protestant circles. While still teaching full-time at West Baden, Hardon became a visiting professor invited to teach Catholic theology at several Protestant seminaries and colleges including Bethany School of Theology, Lutheran School of Theology, and Seabury-Western Divinity School.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Janaro writes:\n\n{{quote|In this work he saw an opportunity to share the fullness of the faith with those baptized in Christ who, because of the circumstances of history, time and place, or culture, had yet to receive a complete understanding and appreciation of the Christian faith and of the Church that extends the power and presence of Jesus Christ.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />}}\n\nThe novelty of the situation was not lost on his Protestant colleagues either, and upon his acceptance of a position at Seabury-Western Divinity school, the Anglican Archbishop of Canterbury sent a personal representative to mark the event - \"the first time in history an Anglican/Episcopalian seminary had appointed a teacher who was a member of the once hated and feared Society of Jesus.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Hardon also served as an advisor to the Second Vatican Council on discussions about liturgy.<ref name=\"Pew\" />\n\nBetween 1962 and 1967 Fr. Hardon taught Roman Catholicism and Comparative Religion at Western Michigan University. He released his book ''Religions of the World'' in 1963. By 1967 he returned to teaching Jesuit scholastics at two Jesuit theological schools in Illinois while working as a visiting professor at St. Paul University in Ottawa, where he taught furloughed missionaries classes in [[missiology]]. At this time he also began work for the Congregations for Religious and the Clergy in Rome to implement the renewal laid out in the documents of [[Vatican II]].<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nIn 1969 Hardon assisted in the founding of a union of religious called the Consortium Perfectae Caritatis. In 1971 he helped found the Institute on Religious Life. That same year Hardon and nine other notable American Catholics were summoned by [[Camaldolese]] abbot [[Ugo Modotti]] acting on behalf of [[Pope Paul VI]]. The group was tasked to create a Catholic media organization and met three times a year for periods of two to three days. Hardon told an interviewer this was because \"the Holy Father's mission was very clear: American Catholics must get some control of the media of social communication; otherwise, the pope feared for the survival of the Church in our country.\"<ref name=\"Inter\" /> A year later Modotti informed Hardon that the Pope had accepted his recommendation to replace him with Hardon should any thing befall the Abbot. Two weeks later Modotti was found dead in his bed and Hardon took over the mission.<ref name=\"Inter\" />\n\nIn 1972, Hardon furthered his media apostolate by founding Mark Communications in Canada. Through his work with the papacy he was later asked by Paul VI to start Pontifical Catechetical Institutes in the United States to ensure the correct catechetical formation of religious educators. Hardon assisted and supported those establishing these organizations, especially Msgr. Eugene Kevane.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nIn 1974 Hardon became a professor at St. John's University in New York City at the Institute for Advanced Studies in Catholic Doctrine. At this time he worked with the Sisters of Notre Dame of Chardon, Ohio to make ''Christ Our Life'', a series of religious textbooks for elementary students.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHardon continued to have health problems throughout his life. In 1981 he had a quadruple bypass at a hospital in Chicago, which would be his seventeenth hospitalization since joining the Jesuits.<ref name=Sacrifice/>\n\n== Controversy ==\nWhile teaching at St. John's, Hardon reacted to a woman's question about his thoughts on the [[Enneagram of Personality]]. He responded with an article listing his objections to the concept, viewing it as a New Age process dangerous to the Catholic faith. Soon after he was summoned to appear before his Jesuit superior to speak on the matter, at the conclusion of the meeting he was informed he would be forbidden to teach at any Jesuit institution.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> At the time of his death Hardon had not been allowed to teach at a Jesuit school for sixteen years. He viewed this as persecution for teaching the faith and saw it as \"[[Christian martyrs#Degrees of martyrdom|white martyrdom]]\" and when recalling it would advise his listeners that they should be willing to suffer for the true doctrines of Catholicism.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Hardon was also rebuffed by the chancery of the Archdiocese of Detroit who refused to use any of his books in their catechetical materials and he was never invited to their conferences and seminars - though he was in high demand across the rest of the nation.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> The conservative Catholic newspaper ''[[The Wanderer (newspaper)|The Wanderer]]'' reported that Fr. Patrick Halfpenny, vice-rector of Sacred Heart Major Seminary in Detroit, had a standing order at ''The Michigan Catholic'' (the diocesan newspaper of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit|Archdiocese of Detroit]]) that Hardon's picture was not to be printed and also that if his name was to be mentioned at all it would be in the smallest font possible, due to Halfpenny's belief that \"He's divisive.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> ''The Wanderer'' also pointed out that at the Mass celebrating the 50th anniversary of his ordination at Assumption Grotto in Detroit, though attended by many friends, not a single Jesuit other than Hardon was there.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\n== Work ==\nFather Hardon was a very prominent member of the [[Jesuit]] community, which is known for its academic rigor, and wrote over forty books<ref name=\"Wanderer\">{{cite news|title=Fr. Hardon, A \"One Man Army Of God\"|author=Paul Likoudis|publisher=The Wanderer|location=St Paul, MN|year=2000|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=3321|accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> on religion and [[theology]],<ref name=\"Review\">{{cite news|title=Late priest with local roots on path toward sainthood| first= Bill| last= Zlatos| url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-29423929| newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]| date=18 August 2011| accessdate=2012-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/publications |title=Publications &#124; Father John A. Hardon, SJ |publisher=Hardonsj.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-18}}</ref> including ''[[The Catholic Catechism (Hardon)|Catholic Catechism: A Contemporary Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'' (1975), a defining volume of Catholic orthodoxy; and the ''Modern Catholic Dictionary'' (1980), a major Catholic reference dictionary published after the [[Second Vatican Council]] (1962\u20131965). In addition to his own works Hardon contributed to six encyclopedias.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHardon had a close working relationship with [[Pope Paul VI]], engaging in several initiatives at the Pope's request, including his authoring of ''The Catholic Catechism''. Paul VI apparently displeased with the controversial [[Dutch Catechism]] and in line with his letter ''Solemni Hac Liturgia'' (Credo of the people of God) requested that Hardon produce a volume to synthesize what Catholics must believe and present it in the English language.<ref name=\"McDermott\" />\n\nFather Hardon's work ''The Catholic Catechism'' was a significant post\u2013[[Second Vatican Council|Vatican II]] work in the sense that it essentially brought modern Catholic teaching and faith into one book, unlike any other before. At the time of his death it had sold over 150,000 in hardback, and as a 623-page paperback had reached its 26th printing selling over one million copies.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />  It served as the normative standard until the publishing of 1992's ''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'', which is the official codified teaching of the Catholic Church, promulgated by [[Pope John Paul II]]. Hardon served as a consultant for the drafting of that document.\n\nHardon kept to a demanding work schedule, especially during the creation of the 1992 ''Catechism''. At that time, once daily demands for his advice as a local spiritual director lessened (around five or six pm), he would write and organize material and continue to work into the night (where upon it would be morning in Rome). He often received phone calls at this time from [[Pope Benedict XVI|Cardinal Ratzinger]] who sought his advice and input to fine tune the ''Catechism''.<ref name=\"McDermott\">{{cite video|title = Servant of God - Fr. John Hardon, S.J.|url=http://vimeo.com/17851700|author=Fr. Robert T. McDermott|publisher=St. Louis Review}}</ref> Ratzinger had a good relationship with Hardon which included sending him notes of thanks for his assistance in the faith.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/node/36|title=note from Ratzinger to Hardon}}</ref>\n\nHardon had sympathy for those attracted to Catholic groups (such as the [[Society of St. Pius X]]) that strenuously objected to portions of Vatican II documents, \"but he never for a moment accepted the premise that a schismatic act was ever justified.\"<ref name=\"Armstrong\" />\n\nHardon was also a major contributor to Catholic newspapers and magazines and was executive editor of ''The Catholic Faith'' magazine.<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />\n\nHardon founded several Catholic organizations, which include ''Inter Mirifica'' (a name taken from Vatican II's decree on social communication), the Marian Catechists (a catechist formation program following the teachings of St. Ignatius),<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> and Holy Trinity Apostolate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.holytrinityapostolate.com/about/founding.html |title=Holy Trinity Apostolate |publisher=Holy Trinity Apostolate |date= |accessdate=2012-08-11}}</ref> He also served as an adviser to many Catholic organizations, including Catholics United for Faith.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nFather Hardon participated in various apostolates to religious communities.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> In the early 1980s, Pope John Paul II instructed [[Mother Teresa of Calcutta]] to have her order evangelize the poor in addition to looking after their material needs.<ref>{{cite web|title=The History of the Apostolate|publisher=Marian Catechist Apostolate|url=http://www.mariancatechist.com/history.html}}</ref> When she stated she didn't know where to begin such an endeavor, the Pope referred her to [[Pope Benedict XVI|Cardinal Ratzinger]], who called upon Hardon to instruct her [[Missionaries of Charity]].<ref name=\"Inter\">{{cite web|title=An Interview with Fr. Hardon|author=Anita C. Crane|url=http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/Fr_Hardon/Fr_Hardon_001.htm|year=2003|publisher=Inter Mirifica}}</ref> To fill this need Hardon wrote a catechetical course for Mother Teresa's order. The course later was adapted and used to create two catechetical home study courses for lay Catholics. In 1985 Hardon founded the Marian Catechist Apostolate, an organization that uses these home study courses to provide catechetical formation to lay people in order to prepare them for [[Catholic Catechist|catechetical]] ministry.<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />\n\nHardon also assisted Catholic home schoolers, and worked with Eternal Life of Bardstown, Kentucky, where he recorded several audio lectures on Catholic topics beginning in 1988.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> His first series for Eternal Life was against contraception which he viewed, in line with other conservative Catholics, as what \"greased the skids for the culture of death\" - seeing it as the source for acceptance of abortion and assisted suicide, all of which are condemned by Catholicism.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> After that series he recorded lectures on the [[Spiritual Exercises of Ignatius of Loyola|Ignatian Exercises]], followed by other programs \"including [[Apostles' Creed|The Apostles' Creed]], [[The Eucharist#Ritual and liturgy|The Eucharist]], Catholic Sexual Morality, and Angels and Devils.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Due to problems with his voice, including long pauses, the recordings were digitally remastered to make him more audible by Ed Wolfrum who previously worked as a Motown music engineer.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHe was known to be devoted to the Catholic practice of [[Eucharistic adoration]], spending at least three hours a day praying before the [[Blessed Sacrament]].<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHardon was a major force in establishing the \"Call to Holiness\" conference, which was held annually in a suburb of [[Detroit, Michigan]]. The initial conference was held in the late 1990s to counter a nearby conference held the same weekend by the liberal Catholic group [[Call to Action]].<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite web|date=April 18, 2006|title=Fr. John A. Hardon, S.J.: Servant of God (1914-2000)|url=http://socrates58.blogspot.com/2006/04/fr-john-hardon-sj-servant-of-god-1914.html|author=Dave Armstrong}}</ref> Hardon also played a key role in the conversion of [[Dave Armstrong (Catholic apologist)|Dave Armstrong]] who went from being a Protestant to becoming a Catholic apologist.<ref name=\"Armstrong\" />\n\nHardon spent his last years working from an office on the grounds of the Assumption Grotto in Detroit serving as a spiritual director.<ref>{{cite web|title=The \"Fr. John Hardon Years at Grotto\" comes to a close as his library moves to Missouri|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2007/11/fr-john-hardon-years-at-grotto-comes-to.html|date=November 3, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Possible beatification ==\nAfter suffering from several illnesses, Father Hardon died from bone cancer at the Jesuits' Colombiere Center in [[Clarkston, Michigan]] on December 30, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Giant Of Faith Passes To God|author=Barbara Middleton|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=4173}}</ref> William J. Smith, who worked with Hardon at Eternal Life, reported that in the priest's final weeks, Hardon \"suffered tremendous physical pain, but he made himself 'a true [[victim soul]].'\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> He willed that at his death his extensive library and correspondence would go to Archbishop Raymond L. Burke.<ref>{{cite web|title=News about Fr. John A. Hardon - The archive, the guild, and a blessing...|date=October 3, 2009|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2009/10/news-about-fr-john-hardon-archive-guild.html}}</ref> Each year Catholics in the Detroit area have a memorial Mass said for Hardon on December 30.<ref>{{cite web|date=January 25, 2010|title=Memorial Mass for Servant of God, Rev. John A. Hardon SJ|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2010/01/photopost-december-30-2009-memorial.html}}</ref>\n\nThere is interest among some Catholics for his [[canonization]], and a Church-sanctioned prayer for that cause has been written. Cardinal [[Raymond Leo Burke|Raymond Burke]], when he was serving as the Archbishop of St. Louis and was the national director of the Marian Catechist Apostolate (began by Hardon), initiated Father Hardon's cause for canonization in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2006/09/national-catholic-register-st-john.html|title=St. John Hardon?|publisher=National Catholic Register|date=August 13, 2006|author=Joseph Pronechen}}</ref> Father Robert McDermott, a former student of Hardon's, was the postulator for the cause until moving to [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]], where he serves as associate pastor at Our Lady of Mount Carmel Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olmckenosha.org/staff|title=OLMC Staff|publisher=Archdiocese of Milwaukee|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> An effort is underway to establish a Father Hardon library and study center at the [[Shrine of Our Lady of Guadalupe]] in [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]].\n\nA concern for Hardon's cause for canonization arose in early 2012 when documents concerning fellow Jesuit Donald McGuire surfaced and were featured in a story by Peter Jamison in the San Francisco Weekly. McGuire was arrested on charges of sex-abuse in 2005 and found guilty of sexually molesting boys in federal and state courts. An article in SF Weekly reported that during a visit to Saint John Vianney, Hardon had a frank conversation with McGuire in which the latter admitted to taking showers with his alleged victim, asking the boy to massage his body, and allowing him to possess pornography in the room they shared while traveling. McGuire denied additional allegations that he had touched the boy's genitals and watched him masturbate. Hardon was apparently satisfied with what he heard. As he wrote to Schaeffer, \"Regarding showering, Fr. Don said that it was true, but the picture is not one of a lingering sensual experience. It was rather the picture of two firemen, responding to an emergency, one of whom was seriously handicapped and in need of support and care from the other.\" On the body rubs: \"Regarding the massages, Fr. Don said they were done with attention to modesty and were necessary to relieve spasm at the 4th-5th lumbar disc and the right leg, involving the sciatic nerve.\" (The fourth and fifth lumbar vertebrae are at the bottom of the spine, just above the buttocks.) And the dirty magazines: \"Regarding pornography Fr. Don said that there were Playboy and Penthouse magazines, which he neither got nor threw away.\" Hardon concluded in the letter, \"I do not believe there was any conscious and deliberate sexual perversity.\" He added, \"I do believe Fr. McGuire was acting on principles which, though objectively defensible, were highly imprudent.\" He told McGuire's bosses that he 'should be prudently allowed to engage in priestly ministry.'\u2026The situation is aggravated since McGuire went on to abuse more children after suggestions to return him to ministry were heeded.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2012-01-11/news/mother-teresa-catholic-church-john-hardon-donald-mcguire-child-abuse-jesuits/2/|title=Tainted Saint: Mother Teresa Defended Pedophile Priest|author=Peter Jamison|date=January 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''All My Liberty''\n* ''The Treasury of Catholic Wisdom''\n* ''A Prophet for the Priesthood''\n* ''With Us Today: On the Real Presence of Jesus Christ in the Eucharist''\n* ''The History of Eucharistic Adoration''\n* ''Modern Catholic Dictionary''\n* ''Theology of Prayer''\n* ''Spiritual Life in the Modern World''\n* ''Salvation and Sanctification''\n* ''Holiness in the Church''\n* ''The Faith''\n* ''History and Theology of Grace: The Catholic Teaching on Divine Grace''\n* ''The Question and Answer Catholic Catechism'', [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1981. {{ISBN|978-0-385-13664-8}}\n* ''The Catholic Catechism: A Contemporary Catechism of the Teachings of the Catholic Church'', Doubleday, 1975. {{ISBN|978-0-385-50819-3}}\n* ''Retreat with the Lord: A Popular Guide to the Spiritual Exercises of Ignatius of Loyola''\n* ''The Pocket Catechism'', [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-385-24293-6}}\n* ''The Pocket Catholic Dictionary: Abridged Edition of a Modern Catholic Dictionary'', [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1985. {{ISBN|978-0-385-23238-8}}\n* ''The Catholic Lifetime Reading Plan''\n* ''Catholic Prayer book''\n* ''Marian Catechist Manual''\n* ''Christianity in the Twentieth Century'', St. Paul Editions, 1977.\n* ''Religions of the World''\n\n== References ==\n;Specific references\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Other sources\n* [http://www.therealpresence.org/ Tribute page]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/archives.htm#nav List of on-line articles]\n* Archbishop Raymond L. Burke, [https://web.archive.org/web/20111114002709/http://www.mariancatechist.com/burke/rechristianize.html \"Re-Christianize America: Become a Marian Catechist\"]\n* [http://www.hardonsj.org Father John Hardon, SJ Archive and Guild]\n* [http://www.therealpresence.org/dictionary/adict.htm Modern Catholic Dictionary by Father John A. Hardon, S.J.] - Reprinted by the website of the Real Presence Association (with the written permission of Eternal Life).\n\n{{Canonization}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= United States |portal4= Saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardon, John}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American Jesuits]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious writers]]\n[[Category:Catholicism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:American Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Loyola University Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:John Carroll University alumni]]\n[[Category:History of Catholicism in Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Clarkston, Michigan]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = [[Servant of God]] <br> John Anthony Hardon, [[Society of Jesus|S.J.]]\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1914|6|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Midland, Pennsylvania|Midland]], [[Pennsylvania (state)|Pennsylvania]], United States\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2000|12|30|1914|6|18|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Clarkston, Michigan|Clarkston]], [[Michigan (state)|Michigan]], United States\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| occupation         = Priest\n| title              = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| networth           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n{{jesuit}}\n\n'''John Anthony Hardon''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Society of Jesus|SJ]]}} (June 18, 1914 \u2013 December 30, 2000) was an American [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] [[priest]], writer, and [[theologian]]. He is recognized by the [[Catholic Church]] as a [[Servant of God]]<ref name=\"Register\">{{cite news| title=The Cause for Father Hardon: Sanctity Made in America, Part 2| first=Charlotte| last=Hays| url=http://www.ncregister.com/site/article/the-cause-for-father-hardon/| newspaper=[[National Catholic Register]]| date=29 October 2010|accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJohn Anthony Hardon was born in 1914 to a devout Catholic family in [[Midland, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" /> When he was a year old, his 27-year-old father died in an industrial accident when the scaffolding collapsed under him as he moved to secure a steel beam dangling dangerously over his co-workers.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /><ref name=\"Pew\">{{cite web|title=Father Hardon will indeed be a hard act to follow|url=http://www.dailycatholic.org/issue/2001Jan/jan5ed.htm|date=January 5, 2001|publisher=Catholic Pewpoint}}</ref> After the accident Hardon was raised by his 26-year-old mother Anna (n\u00e9e Jevin) Hardon, who never remarried \"out of concern for the influence a possible stepfather might have on her son's vocation.\"<ref name=\"Register\" /><ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> They moved to [[Cleveland, Ohio]],<ref name=\"Review\"/> where they lived \"in the shadows of the iron and steel mills\".<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> John Janaro, a biographer of Hardon, described Anna as \"a woman of deep faith, a [[Third Order of Saint Francis|Franciscan tertiary]] who embraced her poverty and her difficult circumstances with courage and grace.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Anna \"attended daily Mass and received Holy Communion\" and her home \"had sacred pictures, a family holy water font, and a good deal of spiritual conversation.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> The Hardons could not afford a telephone and \"in fact they seldom bought a newspaper.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ewtn.com/library/PRIESTS/HARDON.TXT|title=Fr. John Hardon|author=John Janaro|publisher=EWTN}}</ref>\n\nHardon was Anna's only child, and she supported him by cleaning offices in Cleveland, often working nights. Janaro reports that as a child Hardon was \"willful and self-possessed; he was determined that no one was going to tell him what to do\"; but he was soon affected by his mother's devoted example.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Hardon would often recall that his mother told him that she \"taught him to kneel before he could walk\" and the very purpose of knees \"are for kneeling to pray before God\".<ref name=\"Pew\" /> When he was four, Anna took him to his first all night vigil at Our Lady of Consolation parish in Carey, Ohio.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> She made a bed for him on the first pew, and prayed throughout the night on her knees as he slept.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> At the age of six he was instructed by a Sister Benedicta who told her students \"Whatever you ask Our Lord on your First Communion day, you will receive.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> That same year as he received First Holy Communion Hardon made a request to Jesus, \"Make me a priest.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Thereafter the young Hardon attended daily Mass with his mother.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> At the age of eight he received the sacrament of Confirmation calling on the Holy Spirit to give him \"the grace of martyrdom.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" />\n\nFor added income Hardon's mother took in two young [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] girls as boarders<ref name=\"Pew\" /> named Judith and Susan.<ref name=Real>{{cite web|title=Retreat on the Credo, Faith in the Holy Catholic Church and the Communion of Saints|author=Fr. John A. Hardon, S.J.|url=http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/Church_Dogma/Church_Dogma_052.htm}}</ref> Young Hardon at the age of three<ref name=Real/> protested that he had to abstain from meat on Friday but the boarders, which he called his \"sisters\" did not. In response his mother gave the girls a choice saying \"My boy is growing up: he's asking embarrassing questions. Would you mind either abstaining from eating meat on Friday or find yourselves somewhere else to board?\"<ref name=Real/> The girls choose to abstain.<ref name=Real/> After having them get permission from their minister they were included in the fast.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> It was this early relationship with these borders who were \"staunch Lutherans\" (who lived with them for at least eight years<ref name=Real/>) that Hardon would later cite as affecting his thinking, recalling in later life \"Years before the Ecumenical Movement I had come to respect and cherish Protestants.\"<ref name=Real/>\n\n=== Early schooling ===\nHardon excelled in schooling and was often at the top of his classes at St. Wendelin School (which he had to walk two miles to reach).<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />  His ability to hold the attention of a crowd was seen early when in sixth grade he gave a one-man show to his class entitled \"Pockets\" and \"For one solid hour he kept the audience laughing with his explanations of what he carried in his pockets.\"<ref name=\"Pew\" />\n\nDuring a Church History class in eighth grade Hardon was inspired on hearing about the preaching of [[Peter Canisius|St. Peter Canisius]], a Jesuit priest in the 16th century who combated the [[Protestant Reformation]] in Germany. Through this Hardon became impressed with the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] order.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHis mother did not have the funds to send him to a Jesuit High School, so he attended the diocesan high school of Cathedral Latin 15 miles from his home where he was taught by the [[Marist Brothers|Brothers of Mary]].<ref name=\"hardonsj\">{{cite web|title=Rev. John A. Hardon - Biography|author=Dr. Elizabeth Mitchell|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/biography}}</ref>\n\nWorrying about leaving his mother on her own Hardon did not seriously consider the priesthood immediately after high school.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Upon graduation \"With the help of savings his mother had put aside specifically for his future\" he attended [[John Carroll University]], a Jesuit university in a suburb of Cleveland.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> To travel there from his mother's home he had to ride the streetcar \"a distance of three to four hours daily.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" />\n\nDuring his first two years of college, Hardon intended to become a medical doctor. At University, he came even more strongly under the influence of the Jesuits. Janaro writes:\n\n{{quote|The Jesuit presence had a profound impact on him. There was a certain strength about the Jesuits, a \"manliness\" that John had never experienced at home because he never knew his father. Also their mental discipline impressed him; it motivated him to major in philosophy and it began to shape his approach to spirituality through the direction of Father LeMay, a brilliant and discerning man who saw in John great potential.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />}}\n\nElizabeth Mitchell writes that \"under the guidance of his priestly adviser, Hardon began, in his third year of studies, to discern more clearly his own call to the priesthood\".<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />  It was LeMay who guided Hardon to change \"his course of studies to include Latin, philosophy, and college theology.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Hardon continued his studies until he earned his Bachelor of Arts degree from John Carrol University in 1936.<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />\n\n=== Entering the Jesuits ===\nIt did not appear that he would be able to join the Jesuits due to his mother's worsening health, whom he felt duty bound to look after. Seeking both to fulfill his duty to his mother and to serve others, he had applied and been accepted to Ohio State Medical School.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />  While he felt that he did not have a vocation to the priesthood, Fr. LeMay, his Jesuit spiritual adviser, \"did not agree with John's assessment of his situation\" and held that \"John did indeed have a priestly vocation\".<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> His mother, aware that his concern for her health was influencing his decision, told him that \"the very same God who was calling him would guard every hair on his mother's head.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> She also told him \"if the reason he was going to marry was so that she would not be alone without anyone to care for her, he was not to be concerned.\"<ref name=\"Pew\" /> Considering his dream of matrimony \"the thought of marriage and family was overwhelmed by a realization of the spiritual family that springs up around a priest who brings the life of Christ to so many people.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nHardon announced his decision to pursue the priesthood to a girl named Jo who had been his friend since grade school when they sat next to each other.<ref name=\"Pew\" /> They had been dating seriously and discussed marriage on several occasions<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> and Hardon had \"weighed the possibility of becoming engaged.\"<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> He broke the news to her at a restaurant in downtown Cleveland.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Jo did not take the news well, breaking down in tears and crying throughout the meal.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon entered the Jesuit novitiate on September 1, 1936, \"breaking the heart of a girl he loved, and loved him in return.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\"/>\n\nHardon's health difficulties continued he later recalled \"When I entered the Novitiate, in one month they put me in the hospital I thought they were gonna throw me out of the order.\"<ref name=Sacrifice>{{cite web|title=What is Sacrifice?|author=John Hardon|url=http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/Mass/Mass_010.htm|date=August 3, 1982}}</ref> Hardon recovered and continued his studies.\n\nTwo months into his novitiate Hardon confessed to Fr. LeMay that he felt he had abandoned his mother when she needed him most. LeMay told him \"John, you belong in the Society of Jesus. What you are experiencing is a temptation. Put it out of your\nmind.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> To avoid further temptations Hardon continued regularly to correspond with his mother but scrupulously avoided visiting her for seven years until ordered to do so by his superior.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon was deeply affected by the accidental drowning of a fellow seminarian when a group of them were on a summer lakeshore vacation.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> As a result of this he refused to take vacations for the rest of his life.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\n== Priesthood ==\nHaving [[Jesuit formation|entered the Society of Jesus as a novice]] on September 1, 1936 Hardon took a special interest in theology and teaching while studying at West Baden College in [[West Baden Springs, Indiana]]. During these studies he produced his first published article in 1941 concerning the study of Latin. Worrying that his love of theology might lead him to pursue it out of his own willfulness at the cost of obedience he \"determined not to request further theological study; he would leave the determination of his future completely in the hands of the Holy Spirit.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon continued to study and obtained a master's degree in philosophy at [[Loyola University Chicago]] in 1941.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" />\n\nOn June 18, 1947 (his 33rd birthday) he was ordained to the priesthood with his mother in attendance.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> The two Lutheran boarders of Hardon's childhood had remained close to the family and attended his ordination<ref name=Real/> and first Mass.<ref name=\"hardonsj\" /> Within a year of seeing her son enter the priesthood Hardon's mother died.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nHardon took it as a sign of divine favor when his superiors, with no prompting from him, ordered him to attend the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in [[Rome]] to continue his study of theology (from 1949 to 1951).<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /><ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nWhile studying at Rome, he was appointed director of the graduate library. At one point his superior ordered him to retrieve all of the volumes held on loan by other graduate students that were [[Index Librorum Prohibitorum|declared heretical]] by the Catholic Church. Hardon later recalled:\n\n{{quote|Before I had retrieved one-half of the heretical books, I had become the agent of orthodoxy and therefore the sworn enemy of the modernists, who were updating the Catholic faith to its [[Modernism (Roman Catholicism)|modernist]] theology. I had doors slammed in my face. I lost friends whom I had considered believers....[this experience] taught me that the faith I had so casually learned could be preserved only by the price of a living martyrdom. This faith, I was to find out, is a precious treasure that cannot be preserved except at a heavy price. The price is nothing less than to confess what so many others either openly or covertly denied.\"<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />}}\n\nHe received his [[Doctor of Sacred Theology]] degree from the Gregorian University after finishing his doctoral dissertation on St. [[Robert Bellarmine]] entitled ''A Comparative Study of Bellarmine's Doctrine on the Relation of Sincere Non-Catholics to the Catholic Church''. Later in his life, he stated, \u201cI could not have chosen a better subject in preparation for a lifetime of teaching Catholic doctrine.\u201d<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/biography |title=Biography &#124; Father John A. Hardon, SJ |publisher=Hardonsj.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-18}}</ref> That same year, 1951, he received the Papal Medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ordained to Sacrifice|url=http://credo.stormloader.com/Saints/hardon.htm|access-date=2012-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020809152359/http://credo.stormloader.com/Saints/hardon.htm|archive-date=2002-08-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDue to lifelong health problems, including asthma, Hardon was forced to return to America in 1951, where he joined the faculty of West Baden College teaching theology to Jesuit students. Hardon was denied his request to be a missionary to post-War Japan (at the newly opened Jesuit University in Tokyo) due to his health.<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Determined to be of some service for this endeavor, Hardon began to study [[comparative religion]].<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> During his studies of oriental religions he believed there were \"not only areas that were compatible with Christianity but also sections of thought that were clearly influenced in a direct manner by contact with the Christian message.\"<ref name=\"EWTN\" /> Hardon began using his extensive knowledge of Asian customs and religions to train missionaries for that region.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nDuring this time Hardon pronounced his final vows on February 2, 1953 including the special [[Fourth vow|Jesuit vow of unwavering fidelity]] to the pope.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nIn an effort to understand Protestantism he worked on a book released in 1956 entitled ''Protestant Churches in America'', which was met with critical acclaim even among Protestant circles. While still teaching full-time at West Baden, Hardon became a visiting professor invited to teach Catholic theology at several Protestant seminaries and colleges including Bethany School of Theology, Lutheran School of Theology, and Seabury-Western Divinity School.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Janaro writes:\n\n{{quote|In this work he saw an opportunity to share the fullness of the faith with those baptized in Christ who, because of the circumstances of history, time and place, or culture, had yet to receive a complete understanding and appreciation of the Christian faith and of the Church that extends the power and presence of Jesus Christ.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />}}\n\nThe novelty of the situation was not lost on his Protestant colleagues either, and upon his acceptance of a position at Seabury-Western Divinity school, the Anglican Archbishop of Canterbury sent a personal representative to mark the event - \"the first time in history an Anglican/Episcopalian seminary had appointed a teacher who was a member of the once hated and feared Society of Jesus.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Hardon also served as an advisor to the Second Vatican Council on discussions about liturgy.<ref name=\"Pew\" />\n\nBetween 1962 and 1967 Fr. Hardon taught Roman Catholicism and Comparative Religion at Western Michigan University. He released his book ''Religions of the World'' in 1963. By 1967 he returned to teaching Jesuit scholastics at two Jesuit theological schools in Illinois while working as a visiting professor at St. Paul University in Ottawa, where he taught furloughed missionaries classes in [[missiology]]. At this time he also began work for the Congregations for Religious and the Clergy in Rome to implement the renewal laid out in the documents of [[Vatican II]].<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nIn 1969 Hardon assisted in the founding of a union of religious called the Consortium Perfectae Caritatis. In 1971 he helped found the Institute on Religious Life. That same year Hardon and nine other notable American Catholics were summoned by [[Camaldolese]] abbot [[Ugo Modotti]] acting on behalf of [[Pope Paul VI]]. The group was tasked to create a Catholic media organization and met three times a year for periods of two to three days. Hardon told an interviewer this was because \"the Holy Father's mission was very clear: American Catholics must get some control of the media of social communication; otherwise, the pope feared for the survival of the Church in our country.\"<ref name=\"Inter\" /> A year later Modotti informed Hardon that the Pope had accepted his recommendation to replace him with Hardon should any thing befall the Abbot. Two weeks later Modotti was found dead in his bed and Hardon took over the mission.<ref name=\"Inter\" />\n\nIn 1972, Hardon furthered his media apostolate by founding Mark Communications in Canada. Through his work with the papacy he was later asked by Paul VI to start Pontifical Catechetical Institutes in the United States to ensure the correct catechetical formation of religious educators. Hardon assisted and supported those establishing these organizations, especially Msgr. Eugene Kevane.<ref name=\"EWTN\" />\n\nIn 1974 Hardon became a professor at St. John's University in New York City at the Institute for Advanced Studies in Catholic Doctrine. At this time he worked with the Sisters of Notre Dame of Chardon, Ohio to make ''Christ Our Life'', a series of religious textbooks for elementary students.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHardon continued to have health problems throughout his life. In 1981 he had a quadruple bypass at a hospital in Chicago, which would be his seventeenth hospitalization since joining the Jesuits.<ref name=Sacrifice/>\n\n== Controversy ==\nWhile teaching at St. John's, Hardon reacted to a woman's question about his thoughts on the [[Enneagram of Personality]]. He responded with an article listing his objections to the concept, viewing it as a New Age process dangerous to the Catholic faith. Soon after he was summoned to appear before his Jesuit superior to speak on the matter, at the conclusion of the meeting he was informed he would be forbidden to teach at any Jesuit institution.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> At the time of his death Hardon had not been allowed to teach at a Jesuit school for sixteen years. He viewed this as persecution for teaching the faith and saw it as \"[[Christian martyrs#Degrees of martyrdom|white martyrdom]]\" and when recalling it would advise his listeners that they should be willing to suffer for the true doctrines of Catholicism.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Hardon was also rebuffed by the chancery of the Archdiocese of Detroit who refused to use any of his books in their catechetical materials and he was never invited to their conferences and seminars - though he was in high demand across the rest of the nation.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> The conservative Catholic newspaper ''[[The Wanderer (newspaper)|The Wanderer]]'' reported that Fr. Patrick Halfpenny, vice-rector of Sacred Heart Major Seminary in Detroit, had a standing order at ''The Michigan Catholic'' (the diocesan newspaper of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit|Archdiocese of Detroit]]) that Hardon's picture was not to be printed and also that if his name was to be mentioned at all it would be in the smallest font possible, due to Halfpenny's belief that \"He's divisive.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> ''The Wanderer'' also pointed out that at the Mass celebrating the 50th anniversary of his ordination at Assumption Grotto in Detroit, though attended by many friends, not a single Jesuit other than Hardon was there.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\n== Work ==\nFather Hardon was a very prominent member of the [[Jesuit]] community, which is known for its academic rigor, and wrote over forty books<ref name=\"Wanderer\">{{cite news|title=Fr. Hardon, A \"One Man Army Of God\"|author=Paul Likoudis|publisher=The Wanderer|location=St Paul, MN|year=2000|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=3321|accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> on religion and [[theology]],<ref name=\"Review\">{{cite news|title=Late priest with local roots on path toward sainthood| first= Bill| last= Zlatos| url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-29423929| newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]| date=18 August 2011| accessdate=2012-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/publications |title=Publications &#124; Father John A. Hardon, SJ |publisher=Hardonsj.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-18}}</ref> including ''[[The Catholic Catechism (Hardon)|Catholic Catechism: A Contemporary Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'' (1975), a defining volume of Catholic orthodoxy; and the ''Modern Catholic Dictionary'' (1980), a major Catholic reference dictionary published after the [[Second Vatican Council]] (1962\u20131965). In addition to his own works Hardon contributed to six encyclopedias.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHardon had a close working relationship with [[Pope Paul VI]], engaging in several initiatives at the Pope's request, including his authoring of ''The Catholic Catechism''. Paul VI apparently displeased with the controversial [[Dutch Catechism]] and in line with his letter ''Solemni Hac Liturgia'' (Credo of the people of God) requested that Hardon produce a volume to synthesize what Catholics must believe and present it in the English language.<ref name=\"McDermott\" />\n\nFather Hardon's work ''The Catholic Catechism'' was a significant post\u2013[[Second Vatican Council|Vatican II]] work in the sense that it essentially brought modern Catholic teaching and faith into one book, unlike any other before. At the time of his death it had sold over 150,000 in hardback, and as a 623-page paperback had reached its 26th printing selling over one million copies.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />  It served as the normative standard until the publishing of 1992's ''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'', which is the official codified teaching of the Catholic Church, promulgated by [[Pope John Paul II]]. Hardon served as a consultant for the drafting of that document.\n\nHardon kept to a demanding work schedule, especially during the creation of the 1992 ''Catechism''. At that time, once daily demands for his advice as a local spiritual director lessened (around five or six pm), he would write and organize material and continue to work into the night (where upon it would be morning in Rome). He often received phone calls at this time from [[Pope Benedict XVI|Cardinal Ratzinger]] who sought his advice and input to fine tune the ''Catechism''.<ref name=\"McDermott\">{{cite video|title = Servant of God - Fr. John Hardon, S.J.|url=http://vimeo.com/17851700|author=Fr. Robert T. McDermott|publisher=St. Louis Review}}</ref> Ratzinger had a good relationship with Hardon which included sending him notes of thanks for his assistance in the faith.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardonsj.org/node/36|title=note from Ratzinger to Hardon}}</ref>\n\nHardon had sympathy for those attracted to Catholic groups (such as the [[Society of St. Pius X]]) that strenuously objected to portions of Vatican II documents, \"but he never for a moment accepted the premise that a schismatic act was ever justified.\"<ref name=\"Armstrong\" />\n\nHardon was also a major contributor to Catholic newspapers and magazines and was executive editor of ''The Catholic Faith'' magazine.<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />\n\nHardon founded several Catholic organizations, which include ''Inter Mirifica'' (a name taken from Vatican II's decree on social communication), the Marian Catechists (a catechist formation program following the teachings of St. Ignatius),<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> and Holy Trinity Apostolate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.holytrinityapostolate.com/about/founding.html |title=Holy Trinity Apostolate |publisher=Holy Trinity Apostolate |date= |accessdate=2012-08-11}}</ref> He also served as an adviser to many Catholic organizations, including Catholics United for Faith.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nFather Hardon participated in various apostolates to religious communities.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> In the early 1980s, Pope John Paul II instructed [[Mother Teresa of Calcutta]] to have her order evangelize the poor in addition to looking after their material needs.<ref>{{cite web|title=The History of the Apostolate|publisher=Marian Catechist Apostolate|url=http://www.mariancatechist.com/history.html}}</ref> When she stated she didn't know where to begin such an endeavor, the Pope referred her to [[Pope Benedict XVI|Cardinal Ratzinger]], who called upon Hardon to instruct her [[Missionaries of Charity]].<ref name=\"Inter\">{{cite web|title=An Interview with Fr. Hardon|author=Anita C. Crane|url=http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/Fr_Hardon/Fr_Hardon_001.htm|year=2003|publisher=Inter Mirifica}}</ref> To fill this need Hardon wrote a catechetical course for Mother Teresa's order. The course later was adapted and used to create two catechetical home study courses for lay Catholics. In 1985 Hardon founded the Marian Catechist Apostolate, an organization that uses these home study courses to provide catechetical formation to lay people in order to prepare them for [[Catholic Catechist|catechetical]] ministry.<ref name=\"Father Hardon S.J.\" />\n\nHardon also assisted Catholic home schoolers, and worked with Eternal Life of Bardstown, Kentucky, where he recorded several audio lectures on Catholic topics beginning in 1988.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> His first series for Eternal Life was against contraception which he viewed, in line with other conservative Catholics, as what \"greased the skids for the culture of death\" - seeing it as the source for acceptance of abortion and assisted suicide, all of which are condemned by Catholicism.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> After that series he recorded lectures on the [[Spiritual Exercises of Ignatius of Loyola|Ignatian Exercises]], followed by other programs \"including [[Apostles' Creed|The Apostles' Creed]], [[The Eucharist#Ritual and liturgy|The Eucharist]], Catholic Sexual Morality, and Angels and Devils.\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> Due to problems with his voice, including long pauses, the recordings were digitally remastered to make him more audible by Ed Wolfrum who previously worked as a Motown music engineer.<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHe was known to be devoted to the Catholic practice of [[Eucharistic adoration]], spending at least three hours a day praying before the [[Blessed Sacrament]].<ref name=\"Wanderer\" />\n\nHardon was a major force in establishing the \"Call to Holiness\" conference, which was held annually in a suburb of [[Detroit, Michigan]]. The initial conference was held in the late 90's to counter a nearby conference held the same weekend by the liberal Catholic group [[Call to Action]].<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite web|date=April 18, 2006|title=Fr. John A. Hardon, S.J.: Servant of God (1914-2000)|url=http://socrates58.blogspot.com/2006/04/fr-john-hardon-sj-servant-of-god-1914.html|author=Dave Armstrong}}</ref> Hardon also played a key role in the conversion of [[Dave Armstrong (Catholic apologist)|Dave Armstrong]] who went from being a Protestant to becoming a Catholic apologist.<ref name=\"Armstrong\" />\n\nHardon spent his last years working from an office on the grounds of the Assumption Grotto in Detroit serving as a spiritual director.<ref>{{cite web|title=The \"Fr. John Hardon Years at Grotto\" comes to a close as his library moves to Missouri|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2007/11/fr-john-hardon-years-at-grotto-comes-to.html|date=November 3, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Possible beatification ==\nAfter suffering from several illnesses, Father Hardon died from bone cancer at the Jesuits' Colombiere Center in [[Clarkston, Michigan]] on December 30, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Giant Of Faith Passes To God|author=Barbara Middleton|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=4173}}</ref> William J. Smith, who worked with Hardon at Eternal Life, reported that in the priest's final weeks, Hardon \"suffered tremendous physical pain, but he made himself 'a true [[victim soul]].'\"<ref name=\"Wanderer\" /> He willed that at his death his extensive library and correspondence would go to Archbishop Raymond L. Burke.<ref>{{cite web|title=News about Fr. John A. Hardon - The archive, the guild, and a blessing...|date=October 3, 2009|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2009/10/news-about-fr-john-hardon-archive-guild.html}}</ref> Each year Catholics in the Detroit area have a memorial Mass said for Hardon on December 30.<ref>{{cite web|date=January 25, 2010|title=Memorial Mass for Servant of God, Rev. John A. Hardon SJ|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2010/01/photopost-december-30-2009-memorial.html}}</ref>\n\nThere is interest among some Catholics for his [[canonization]], and a Church-sanctioned prayer for that cause has been written. Cardinal [[Raymond Leo Burke|Raymond Burke]], when he was serving as the Archbishop of St. Louis and was the national director of the Marian Catechist Apostolate (began by Hardon), initiated Father Hardon's cause for canonization in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://te-deum.blogspot.com/2006/09/national-catholic-register-st-john.html|title=St. John Hardon?|publisher=National Catholic Register|date=August 13, 2006|author=Joseph Pronechen}}</ref> Father Robert McDermott, a former student of Hardon's, was the postulator for the cause until moving to [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]], where he serves as associate pastor at Our Lady of Mount Carmel Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olmckenosha.org/staff|title=OLMC Staff|publisher=Archdiocese of Milwaukee|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> An effort is underway to establish a Father Hardon library and study center at the [[Shrine of Our Lady of Guadalupe]] in [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]].\n\nA concern for Hardon's cause for canonization arose in early 2012 when documents concerning fellow Jesuit Donald McGuire surfaced and were featured in a story by Peter Jamison in the San Francisco Weekly. McGuire was arrested on charges of sex-abuse in 2005 and found guilty of sexually molesting boys in federal and state courts. An article in SF Weekly reported that during a visit to Saint John Vianney, Hardon had a frank conversation with McGuire in which the latter admitted to taking showers with his alleged victim, asking the boy to massage his body, and allowing him to possess pornography in the room they shared while traveling. McGuire denied additional allegations that he had touched the boy's genitals and watched him masturbate. Hardon was apparently satisfied with what he heard. As he wrote to Schaeffer, \"Regarding showering, Fr. Don said that it was true, but the picture is not one of a lingering sensual experience. It was rather the picture of two firemen, responding to an emergency, one of whom was seriously handicapped and in need of support and care from the other.\" On the body rubs: \"Regarding the massages, Fr. Don said they were done with attention to modesty and were necessary to relieve spasm at the 4th-5th lumbar disc and the right leg, involving the sciatic nerve.\" (The fourth and fifth lumbar vertebrae are at the bottom of the spine, just above the buttocks.) And the dirty magazines: \"Regarding pornography Fr. Don said that there were Playboy and Penthouse magazines, which he neither got nor threw away.\" Hardon concluded in the letter, \"I do not believe there was any conscious and deliberate sexual perversity.\" He added, \"I do believe Fr. McGuire was acting on principles which, though objectively defensible, were highly imprudent.\" He told McGuire's bosses that he 'should be prudently allowed to engage in priestly ministry.'\u2026The situation is aggravated since McGuire went on to abuse more children after suggestions to return him to ministry were heeded.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2012-01-11/news/mother-teresa-catholic-church-john-hardon-donald-mcguire-child-abuse-jesuits/2/|title=Tainted Saint: Mother Teresa Defended Pedophile Priest|author=Peter Jamison|date=January 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''All My Liberty''\n* ''The Treasury of Catholic Wisdom''\n* ''A Prophet for the Priesthood''\n* ''With Us Today: On the Real Presence of Jesus Christ in the Eucharist''\n* ''The History of Eucharistic Adoration''\n* ''Modern Catholic Dictionary''\n* ''Theology of Prayer''\n* ''Spiritual Life in the Modern World''\n* ''Salvation and Sanctification''\n* ''Holiness in the Church''\n* ''The Faith''\n* ''History and Theology of Grace: The Catholic Teaching on Divine Grace''\n* ''The Question and Answer Catholic Catechism'', [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1981. {{ISBN|978-0-385-13664-8}}\n* ''The Catholic Catechism: A Contemporary Catechism of the Teachings of the Catholic Church'', Doubleday, 1975. {{ISBN|978-0-385-50819-3}}\n* ''Retreat with the Lord: A Popular Guide to the Spiritual Exercises of Ignatius of Loyola''\n* ''The Pocket Catechism'', [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-385-24293-6}}\n* ''The Pocket Catholic Dictionary: Abridged Edition of a Modern Catholic Dictionary'', [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1985. {{ISBN|978-0-385-23238-8}}\n* ''The Catholic Lifetime Reading Plan''\n* ''Catholic Prayer book''\n* ''Marian Catechist Manual''\n* ''Christianity in the Twentieth Century'', St. Paul Editions, 1977.\n* ''Religions of the World''\n\n== References ==\n;Specific references\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Other sources\n* [http://www.therealpresence.org/ Tribute page]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.therealpresence.org/archives/archives.htm#nav List of on-line articles]\n* Archbishop Raymond L. Burke, [https://web.archive.org/web/20111114002709/http://www.mariancatechist.com/burke/rechristianize.html \"Re-Christianize America: Become a Marian Catechist\"]\n* [http://www.hardonsj.org Father John Hardon, SJ Archive and Guild]\n* [http://www.therealpresence.org/dictionary/adict.htm Modern Catholic Dictionary by Father John A. Hardon, S.J.] - Reprinted by the website of the Real Presence Association (with the written permission of Eternal Life).\n\n{{Canonization}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= United States |portal4= Saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardon, John}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American Jesuits]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious writers]]\n[[Category:Catholicism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:American Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Loyola University Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:John Carroll University alumni]]\n[[Category:History of Catholicism in Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Clarkston, Michigan]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Hardon"}
{"title_page": "Edward Martin (Queens')", "text_new": "'''Edward Martin''', D.D. (died 1662) was an English clergyman, ejected [[List of Presidents of Queens' College, Cambridge|President]] of [[Queens' College, Cambridge]], and at the end of his life [[Dean of Ely]].\n\n==Life==\nA native of [[Cambridgeshire]], he matriculated in the university of Cambridge, as a [[sizar]] of Queens' College, 5 July 1605. He graduated B.A. in 1608\u20139, M. A. in 1612, was elected a Fellow of his college 11 March 1617, and proceeded B.D. in 1621.<ref>{{acad|id=MRTN605E|name=Martin, Edward}}</ref>\n\nIn 1627 he was chaplain to Archbishop [[William Laud]], and he offended the [[Puritan]] party by licensing a book by [[Thomas Jackson (theologian)|Thomas Jackson]], called ''An Historical Narration'', and also by preaching a sermon at [[St. Paul's Cross]] against [[Presbyterianism]]. He became vicar of [[Oakington]] in 1626 and rector of [[Conington, South Cambridgeshire|Conington]], Cambridgeshire, in 1630. He was elected President of Queens' College 16 October 1631, being in the same year created D.D. by royal mandate. He was also rector of the [[Church of St Peter and St Paul, Uppingham]], [[Rutland]], from 1631 to 1637, where he was succeeded by [[Jeremy Taylor]]. In 1638 he was instituted to the rectory of [[Houghton Conquest]], [[Bedfordshire]], and soon afterwards to that of [[Doddington, Cambridgeshire|Doddington]], Cambridgeshire.\n\nIn August 1642 he sent the college plate to the king. [[Oliver Cromwell]] thereupon surrounded several colleges with soldiers, and took away by force the masters of Queens', [[Jesus College, Cambridge|Jesus College]], and [[St. John's College, Cambridge|St. John's College]], and hurrying them to London, incarcerated them in the [[Tower of London]] by order of parliament. Martin was afterwards removed to [[William Petre, 4th Baron Petre|Lord Petre]]'s house in [[Aldersgate Street]], where he drew up the mock petition, entitled his ''Submission to the Covenant.'' Subsequently, he was remanded to [[Ely Place|Ely House]] and other places of confinement for more than five years. In the meanwhile he was ejected from the presidency of Queens' College, and lost all his other preferments.\n\nAbout August 1648 he effected his escape, and went to [[Thorington]], [[Suffolk]], where he resided with Henry Cooke, who had been a member of his college. He assumed the name of Matthews, but was discovered by some soldiers from [[Great Yarmouth|Yarmouth]], was brought to London, and on 23 May 1650 was committed to the [[Gatehouse Prison]] by [[John Bradshaw (judge)|John Bradshaw]], president of the council of state. Ultimately, by some interest with Colonel Wanton, he obtained his release and a pardon for breaking prison. He then returned to Suffolk and resumed his own name; but subsequently he went abroad for seven or eight years, during most of which time he lived at Paris with [[Christopher Hatton, 1st Baron Hatton]]. In 1656 he was resident at [[Utrecht University|Utrecht]] with many other royalists.\n\nReturning to England at the Restoration, he was formally restored to the presidency of Queens' College, on 2 August 1660. He was one of the managers of the [[Savoy Conference]]. In February. 1662 he was nominated to the deanery of Ely, and was installed by proxy, 25 April 1662. He died three days afterwards on 28 April 1662, and was buried in the college chapel.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Martin, Edward}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Queens' College, Cambridge|President of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n  | years  = 1631&ndash;1644\n  | before = [[John Mansell (Cambridge)|John Mansell]]\n  | after  = [[Herbert Palmer (Puritan)|Herbert Palmer]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Queens' College, Cambridge|President of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n  | years  = 1660&ndash;1662\n  | before = [[Thomas Horton (Gresham College)|Thomas Horton]]\n  | after  = [[Anthony Sparrow]]\n}}\n{{end}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Deans of Ely}}\n{{Presidents of Queens' College, Cambridge}}\n{{Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Edward}}\n[[Category:16th-century births]]\n[[Category:1662 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Savoy Conference]]\n[[Category:16th-century English clergy]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Deans of Ely]]\n", "text_old": "'''Edward Martin''', D.D. (died 1662) was an English clergyman, ejected [[List of Presidents of Queens' College, Cambridge|President]] of [[Queens' College, Cambridge]], and at the end of his life [[Dean of Ely]].\n\n==Life==\nA native of [[Cambridgeshire]], he matriculated in the university of Cambridge, as a [[sizar]] of Queens' College, 5 July 1605. He graduated B.A. in 1608-9, M. A. in 1612, was elected a Fellow of his college 11 March 1617, and proceeded B.D. in 1621.<ref>{{acad|id=MRTN605E|name=Martin, Edward}}</ref>\n\nIn 1627 he was chaplain to Archbishop [[William Laud]], and he offended the [[Puritan]] party by licensing a book by [[Thomas Jackson (theologian)|Thomas Jackson]], called ''An Historical Narration'', and also by preaching a sermon at [[St. Paul's Cross]] against [[Presbyterianism]]. He became vicar of [[Oakington]] in 1626 and rector of [[Conington, South Cambridgeshire|Conington]], Cambridgeshire, in 1630. He was elected President of Queens' College 16 October 1631, being in the same year created D.D. by royal mandate. He was also rector of the [[Church of St Peter and St Paul, Uppingham]], [[Rutland]], from 1631 to 1637, where he was succeeded by [[Jeremy Taylor]]. In 1638 he was instituted to the rectory of [[Houghton Conquest]], [[Bedfordshire]], and soon afterwards to that of [[Doddington, Cambridgeshire|Doddington]], Cambridgeshire.\n\nIn August 1642 he sent the college plate to the king. [[Oliver Cromwell]] thereupon surrounded several colleges with soldiers, and took away by force the masters of Queens', [[Jesus College, Cambridge|Jesus College]], and [[St. John's College, Cambridge|St. John's College]], and hurrying them to London, incarcerated them in the [[Tower of London]] by order of parliament. Martin was afterwards removed to [[William Petre, 4th Baron Petre|Lord Petre]]'s house in [[Aldersgate Street]], where he drew up the mock petition, entitled his ''Submission to the Covenant.'' Subsequently he was remanded to [[Ely Place|Ely House]] and other places of confinement for more than five years. In the meanwhile he was ejected from the presidency of Queens' College, and lost all his other preferments.\n\nAbout August 1648 he effected his escape, and went to [[Thorington]], [[Suffolk]], where he resided with Henry Cooke, who had been a member of his college. He assumed the name of Matthews, but was discovered by some soldiers from [[Great Yarmouth|Yarmouth]], was brought to London, and on 23 May 1650 was committed to the [[Gatehouse Prison]] by [[John Bradshaw (judge)|John Bradshaw]], president of the council of state. Ultimately, by some interest with Colonel Wanton, he obtained his release and a pardon for breaking prison. He then returned to Suffolk and resumed his own name; but subsequently he went abroad for seven or eight years, during most of which time he lived at Paris with [[Christopher Hatton, 1st Baron Hatton]]. In 1656 he was resident at [[Utrecht University|Utrecht]] with many other royalists.\n\nReturning to England at the Restoration, he was formally restored to the presidency of Queens' College, on 2 August 1660. He was one of the managers of the [[Savoy Conference]]. In February. 1662 he was nominated to the deanery of Ely, and was installed by proxy, 25 April 1662. He died three days afterwards on 28 April 1662, and was buried in the college chapel.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Martin, Edward}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Queens' College, Cambridge|President of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n  | years  = 1631&ndash;1644\n  | before = [[John Mansell (Cambridge)|John Mansell]]\n  | after  = [[Herbert Palmer (Puritan)|Herbert Palmer]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Queens' College, Cambridge|President of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n  | years  = 1660&ndash;1662\n  | before = [[Thomas Horton (Gresham College)|Thomas Horton]]\n  | after  = [[Anthony Sparrow]]\n}}\n{{end}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Deans of Ely}}\n{{Presidents of Queens' College, Cambridge}}\n{{Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Edward}}\n[[Category:16th-century births]]\n[[Category:1662 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Savoy Conference]]\n[[Category:16th-century English clergy]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Deans of Ely]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Subsequently \u2192 Subsequently,, 1608-9 \u2192 1608\u20139", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Martin_(Queens%27)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Carolina", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in South Carolina, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Carolina\n| width           = \n| image           = COVID-19 Warning Mount Pleasant South Carolina.jpg\n| image_size      = 250\n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Warning sign in [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|Mount Pleasant]]\n| map1            = File:COVID-19 Cases by counties of South Carolina.png\n| legend1         = {{legend|#EC1C24|Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#5C1A27|COVID-19 related deaths}}\n <center>'''''Last updated on April 7, 2020 at 11:00 a.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]'''''</center>\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[South Carolina]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020<br>[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]] and [[Kershaw County, South Carolina|Kershaw]] counties\n| arrival_date    = <!-- or | dates = -->\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 2,232\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 48\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.scdhec.gov/covid19}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[South Carolina]] in March 2020. As of April 6, 2020, the [[South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control]] has confirmed 2,232 cases in the state, resulting in 48 deaths.<ref name=\"DHECcount\">{{cite web |title=Testing & SC Data (COVID-19) {{!}} SCDHEC |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/infectious-diseases/viruses/coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19/testing-sc-data-covid-19 |website=scdhec.gov |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> On April 2, 2020, DHEC announced that the virus had spread to all 46 counties in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 reported in all 46 counties across SC, 4 cases in Laurens County |url=http://www.golaurens.com/news/covid-19-reported-in-all-46-counties-across-sc-4-cases-in-laurens-county/article_49d8a66c-71f9-11ea-9c94-77636b0c19fd.html |website=GoLaurens.Com |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/South Carolina medical cases chart}}\n*'''March 6:''' DHEC announces that two women, one from [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]] and one from [[Kershaw County, South Carolina|Kershaw County]], are under investigation and are presumed to have South Carolina's first cases of [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Feit |first1=Noah |last2=Daprile |first2=Lucas |last3=Fretwell |first3=Sammy |title=First potential coronavirus cases under investigation in South Carolina |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/state/south-carolina/article240838221.html |website=thestate.com |publisher=The State |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 7:''' Tests for the two women return as \"presumptive-positive,\" giving South Carolina its first two cases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riviera |first1=Ray |last2=Phillips |first2=Patrick |title=First possible S.C. novel coronavirus cases detected in Charleston, Kershaw Counties |url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/03/07/first-possible-novel-coronavirus-cases-detected-charleston-kershaw-counties/ |website=live5news.com |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 12:''' \n**The [[South Carolina Independent School Association]] (SCISA) announces that it will be suspending all athletics until April 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Glover |first1=Emery |title=SCISA postpones spring sports in S.C. amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/12/scisa-postpones-spring-sports-sc-amid-coronavirus-concerns/ |website=wistv.com |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[South Carolina Science Olympiad]] announces its decision to cancel its state championship tournaments for both divisions.<ref>{{cite web |title=SC SCIENCE OLYMPIAD |url=https://www.sc-so.org/ |website=sc-so.org |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 13:''' [[Governor of South Carolina|Governor]] [[Henry McMaster]] declares a [[state of emergency]] and orders the closure of all public schools in Kershaw and [[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]] counties for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=S.C. governor declares state of emergency; orders Kershaw, Lancaster county schools to close |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/13/sc-governor-declare-state-emergency-orders-kershaw-lancaster-county-schools-close/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 15:''' Governor McMaster and other officials announce the closure of all public schools in the state until March 31.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ablon |first1=Matthew |title=SC governor shuts down all public schools until March 31 to combat spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.foxcarolina.com/coronavirus/sc-governor-shuts-down-all-public-schools-until-march-to/article_610dca74-66fa-11ea-a3b1-4b468e5adf2d.html |website=FOX Carolina |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=15 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 16:''' \n**A nursing home patient in Lexington County is reported as the first COVID-19 related death in South Carolina.<ref name=\"firstdeath\">{{cite web |title=State of South Carolina Reports First COVID-19 Related Death |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/news-releases/state-south-carolina-reports-first-covid-19-related-death |website=South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=S.C. reports first COVID-19-related death was Lexington Co. nursing home patient |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/16/sc-reports-first-covid-related-death/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[South Carolina High School League]] (SCHSL) suspends all spring sports until April 5.<ref>{{cite web |title=SCHSL suspends all spring sports due to threat of coronavirus |url=https://www.wmbfnews.com/2020/03/16/schsl-suspends-all-spring-sports-due-threat-coronavirus/ |website=wmbfnews.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 17:''' Governor McMaster issues an executive order requiring the mandatory shutdown of dine-in service in restaurants and bars.  The order also includes the delay of state tax deadlines until June 1, the general request of state agencies to waive any restrictive regulations in order to move faster to address the virus, and also prohibits gatherings of more than 50 people at publicly-owned facilities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-10 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-03-17%20eFILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-10%20-%20Directing%20Additional%20Emergency%20Measures%20Due%20to%20COVID-19.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Governor's Update on Coronavirus (COVID-19) | date=March 17, 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hmFB142WyLw |website=YouTube |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 19:''' The Governor issues an additional executive order, ordering non-essential state employees to stay home, emergency measures for unemployment claims and benefits, among other orders, including calling for all public colleges and universities in the state to finish their semesters online.<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-11 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-03-19%20FILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-11%20-%20Additional%20Emergency%20Measures%20%26%20Regulatory%20Relief%20re%20COVID-19.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Governor's Update on Coronavirus (COVID-19) March 19, 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FH-EOGBEzWI |website=YouTube |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=S.C. governor asks colleges to complete semester online as 21 more COVID-19 cases reported |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/19/sc-governor-asks-colleges-complete-semester-online-more-covid-cases-reported/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 20:''' Two deaths are reported, one in Florence County and one in Charleston County, bringing the total for the state to three. Both persons were reported as being elderly and having underlying health conditions.<ref name=\"deaths23\">{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=DHEC: 2 more people in South Carolina die after contracting coronavirus |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/20/dhec-more-people-south-carolina-die-after-contracting-coronavirus/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 21:''' The Governor says that a [[shelter in place]] is \"not under consideration\" at the time, after rumors to the contrary and similar action being taken by other states.<ref>{{cite web |title=S.C. governor: shelter-in-place \"not under consideration\" |url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/21/sc-governor-shelter-in-place-not-under-consideration/ |website=wbtv.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> McMaster also orders local law enforcement to disperse crowds gathered on state beaches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/21/additional-coronavirus-cases-south-carolina-statewide-total-rises/|title=46 additional coronavirus cases in South Carolina, statewide total rises to 173|last=Staff|first=WBTV Web|website=www.wbtv.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*'''March 23:''' \n**DHEC reports two additional deaths, one from Kershaw County (later reclassified to Sumter County) and one from Clarendon County, bringing South Carolina's total to five. Both persons had underlying health conditions.<ref name=\"deaths45\">{{cite web |title=State of South Carolina Reports Two Additional COVID-19 Related Deaths {{!}} SCDHEC |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/news-releases/state-south-carolina-reports-two-additional-covid-19-related-deaths |website=www.scdhec.gov |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Governor McMaster holds a briefing in which he instructs law enforcement to disperse any public gathering of three or more people, with violations of this rule resulting in a misdemeanor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus updates in SC: Gov. McMaster directs law enforcement to break up public gatherings of 3 or more |url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/2020/03/23/coronavirus-updates-sc-heres-what-know-monday-morning/2894988001/ |website=The Greenville News |accessdate=23 March 2020 |language=en |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 24:''' \n**Governor McMaster and State Superintendent of Education Molly Spearman announce that public schools statewide, including colleges and universities, will remain closed through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web |title=SC schools to remain closed through April |url=http://www.golaurens.com/news/sc-schools-to-remain-closed-through-april/article_2deb289e-6e02-11ea-a60b-abceb632d77b.html |website=GoLaurens.Com |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=South Carolina schools will remain closed until the end of April, governor says |url=https://www.wyff4.com/article/south-carolina-schools-will-remain-closed-until-the-end-of-april-governor-says/31916572 |website=WYFF |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The sixth and seventh coronavirus-related deaths are reported by DHEC. One of these was the second death reported from Florence County; this person was reported to have underlying health problems. The other death was reported from Horry County; this person did not have any reported underlying health problems. Additionally, DHEC reported that an individual whose death was originally attributed to Kershaw County actually resided in Sumter County.<ref name=\"deaths67\">{{cite web |title=South Carolina Announces Two Additional Deaths Related to COVID-19 {{!}} SCDHEC |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/index.php/news-releases/south-carolina-announces-two-additional-deaths-related-covid-19 |website=www.scdhec.gov |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 25:''' The death of Jack West, the son of former Governor [[John C. West]], is reported as the eighth in South Carolina and the first from Kershaw County.<ref name=\"death8\">{{cite web |last1=Fretwell |first1=Sammy |title=Coronavirus claims life of lobbyist, son of former South Carolina governor |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/coronavirus/article241397776.html |website=thestate.com |publisher=The State |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 27:'''\n**It is announced that state parks will be closed through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web |title=All SC state parks to close due to COVID-19, park officials say |url=https://www.wyff4.com/article/state-parks-closing-through-april-officials-say/31955615 |website=WYFF |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**President [[Donald Trump]] approves South Carolina's disaster declaration.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pres. Trump approves South Carolina disaster declaration |url=https://www.wbtw.com/news/state-regional-news/pres-trump-approves-south-carolina-disaster-declaration/ |website=WBTW |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''April 1:''' The Governor orders all non-essential businesses closed temporarily.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kalsi |first1=Dal |title=Governor orders 'non-essential' SC businesses in 3 categories to close by 5 p.m. Wednesday |url=https://www.foxcarolina.com/news/governor-orders-non-essential-sc-businesses-in-3-categories-to-close-by-5-p-m/article_1212445a-738d-11ea-af6f-bf7123385b7c.html |website=FOX Carolina |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''April 3:'''\n**The Governor issues two additional executive orders, one ordering the closure of additional non-essential businesses,<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-18 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-04-03%20eFILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-18%20-%20Closure%20of%20Additional%20Non-Essential%20Businesses.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor}}</ref> and the other enforcing lodging and travel restrictions from people traveling from high-risk areas (New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut).<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-19 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-04-03%20eFILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-19%20-%20Lodging%20%26%20Travel%20Restrictions%20for%20Individuals%20from%20High-Risk%20Areas.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor}}</ref>\n**Data of confirmed cases by zip code is first released.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in South Carolina, by Zip CodesCases as of 4/2/2020 at 11:59 PM |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/sites/default/files/media/document/Covid%20Zip%20Analysis%204_3_2020%20No%20Estimates_0.pdf |website=South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n**DHEC releases data of total persons tested by DHEC Public Health Laboratory and, for the first time, data from private laboratories.<ref name=\"DHECcount\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\n[[File:COVID-19 Cases by counties of South Carolina with scale.png|thumb|right|{{legend|#FFDDCC|1\u20135 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|6\u201310 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|11\u201320 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#